<HEADLINE> Strange Paralysis Spreads in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A strange paralysis named Acute
flaccid, a disease which is deadly dangerous to children, is
spreading quickly in Angola, with 20 having reportedly been killed
among the 320 cases registered, local health officials said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The disease firstly spotted in March in Luanda Province, where
most of the victims are found, but the disease have also cropped
up in the neighboring Bengo Province, Benguela Province in central
Angola and the remote Cuando Cubango Province.
</P>
<P>
Victims of the disease are often children under six of age. The
first symptoms of the disease look like that of flu, but patients
will most likely suffer paralysis in their limbs and internal
organs, with some losing their ability to stand up or walk a few
days after the fever is disappeared,

and some even die from lung paralysis.
</P>
<P>
The disease is temporarily named as "acute flaccid paralysis".
</P>
<P>
Doctors in South Africa have discovered, through excrement
test, an infantile paralysis virus that is often found in some
remote areas in Africa. It is believed that the virus must have
been brought into the cities by people displaced from the
prevailing war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
