<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Immunize Children Against Measles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will hold the
National Immunization Day against Measles in September this year
following increased incidence of the disease in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Manager of the Expanded Program on Immunization (EPI),
Carolyne Akim, said in here Wednesday that measles cases have
increased threefold in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
Measles is one of the six children-killing diseases, together
with polio, tuberculosis, tetanus, whooping cough and diphtheria.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, there were 3,000 measle cases reported in the east
African country, while the figure rose to 10,080 by the end of
last year, statistics indicated.
</P>
<P>
No region in the country was spared from the measles outbreak
last year, she said.
</P>
<P>
"We are still receiving reports from various regions and the
number might now be higher due to high rate of outbreaks," Akim
said.
</P>
<P>
She said the EPI program officers are still soliciting funds
for the September exercise which involves vaccination of all
children under five years old, regardless of their immunization
status.
</P>
<P>
Exact date for the exercise will be announced later, she said,
adding that more than one million children under five will be
immunized.
</P>
<P>
Akim said they have started to mobilize people, medication and
equipment, but they still lack in vaccines and human resources.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Akim told a meeting for EPI managers and
surveillance officers from east and southern Africa that some
districts in Tanzania have been unable to control the outbreak of
measles due to poor refrigeration systems for the preservation of
vaccines.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which started Friday in Dar es Salaam, is attended
by participants from Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Uganda, Zambia,
Burundi, Rwanda, Zimbabwe, Malawi, South Africa and Tanzania. It
will end Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
