<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges Parties in Angola to Seek Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council on Wednesday expressed its grave Concern over the
political, military and humanitarian situation in Angola and urged
the parties concerned to seek political resolution to their
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Council was briefed this morning on the
latest developments of the situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Council President for the current month
Alain Dejammet of France said the members of the Council
reiterated that the primary cause of the current crisis in Angola
was the refusal by the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola( UNITA) to comply with the basic provisions of the
Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Council further demanded that UNITA comply with
it obligations to demilitarize and to permit the extension of
states administration to areas under its control.
</P>
<P>
Members of the the Council called on both the Government of
Angola and UNITA to cooperated in improving the humanitarian
situation by guaranteeing access to humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Council expressed their concern at the continued
violation of sanctions against UNITA imposed by the Security
Council and welcomed the intended visit to the region in May by
the chairman of the sanctions committee for Angola.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Council recalled their request to receive
information on the result of investigations into the downing of
the two UN chartered aircraft as well as the crash of the aircraft
in which U.N. Special Representative Alioune Blondin Beye lost his
life.  
</P>
</TEXT>
