<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Reiterates Rejection to U.N. panels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan on Wednesday reiterated Iraq's rejection to three U.N. panels
commissioned with reviewing Iraq's relations with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan stressed that Iraq is not concerned with those panels their
reports submitted to the U.N. Security Council because Iraq was not
consulted on their establishment in the first place.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan made the remarks while touring a industrial products
fair sponsored by the Ministry of Industry and Minerals.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq demands total lifting of the sanctions and condemnation of
the military aggressions waged against it, "said Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
"Implementing the essence of U.N. Resolution 687...is the only
solution" for ending the deadlock between Iraq and the U.N., said
the vice president.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council decided on January 30 to set up three panels
to assess Iraq's disarmamemt progress, its humanitarian situation and
Kuwaiti prisoners of war allegedly detained by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
These three panels are required to make recommendations to the
Security Council before April 15 on what more should be done to
close all those files.
</P>
<P>
The panel in charge of Iraq's disarmament field submitted its
report to the Council early this month in which it recommended that
monitroing,inspection and investigation of Iraq's weapons programs
should continue.
</P>
<P>
U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq have been suspended since the
U.S. and Britain launched four-night airstrikes against Iraq last
December.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council since then has been sharply divided on its
policy toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
While the U.S. and Britain oppose any easing of U.N. sanctions
on Iraq, Russia, China and France want them to be reduced or totally
lifted as an alternative to resuming long-term monitoring of Iraq's
weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
U.N.imposed crippling economic sanctions on Iraq follwoing its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
