<HEADLINE> Namibian, Zambian Presidents Talk on Congo (k) War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Namibian President Sam
Nujoma has described his one-day talks with Zambian President
Frederick Chiluba as "successful".
</P>
<P>
While meeting with Chiluba in the State House in Lusaka
Wednesday, Nujoma said the two countries are interested in finding
a peaceful solution to the conflict in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chiluba said he was very happy that Congolese
President Laurent Kabila has finally agreed to allow the rebels
fighting to topple him to officially take part in the future peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said he would continue to make efforts to arrange a
meeting in Lusaka attended by foreign and defense ministers for
finding a peaceful solution on the issue of DRC.
</P>
<P>
If the first step is a success, it will be followed by a summit
meeting, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba explained that Kabila is merely preparing for the
internal debate that is likely to follow after the signing of a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Before departure at Lusaka international airport, Nujoma said
the leaders in the region would continue to pursue peace in the
DCR.
</P>
<P>
He said the two presidents agreed to encourage Kabila to go
ahead and meet the rebels so that the conflict could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
It was important for the two parties to meet and talk if a
cease-fire is to be signed, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
