<HEADLINE> Arafat Favors Delaying Statehood Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat agreed that a unilateral declaration of Palestinian
statehood should be delayed, South African Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki's office said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki's spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa said Arafat expressed this
view in a meeting with President Nelson Mandela and Mbeki Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Our understanding is that Arafat will postpone the
declaration," Mamoepa told reporters in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"It was our view, shared by Arafat, that the declaration should
be postponed," he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat met Mandela and Mbeki to consult them on the
advisability of going ahead with proclaiming a Palestinian state
on May 4, ahead of the Israeli general election on May 17.
</P>
<P>
Arafat visited South Africa as part of a tour of more than a
dozen countries to discuss the statehood issue.
</P>
<P>
He hinted in Japan last week that he would not make such a
declaration before the Israeli election.
</P>
<P>
Officials said Tuesday that the Palestinian parliament would
meet on April 27 to take a decision on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
