<HEADLINE> NATO Strikes Inflict Huge Damage on Yugoslavia: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav ambassador to Ukraine Gojko
Dapcevich said here Wednesday that NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia over the past three weeks have killed about 500
civilians and injured more than 4,000 people.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the air campaign, NATO forces carried out
about 1,000 air sorties against Yugoslavia and destroyed more than
1,000 economic installations and over 10,000 apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
NATO forces also launched about 1,000 cruise missiles and
dropped more than 3,500 tons of bombs at 180 targets.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the NATO air campaign primarily targeted at
civilian installations which aimed to inflict as much damage as
possible to the Yugoslav economy and intimidate the residents.
</P>
<P>
He cited estimates by foreign experts as saying that NATO's
bombings have cost Yugoslavia more than 200 billion U.S. dollars
in damage. He said the destruction of economic installations have
thrown more than 500,000 people out of work. About two million
people have lost their sources of living.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav ambassador also pointed out that during the NATO's
aggression against Yugoslavia, the ethnic terrorists in the
restive Serbian province of Kosovo intensified their attacks
against Serb policemen and civilians, killing 76 people, most of
them civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
