<HEADLINE> U.S. Reserves Likely to Be Called to Active Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of military reserves
may be called up by U.S. President Bill Clinton to support a major
buildup of NATO air power against Yugoslavia, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Wednesday that several
thousand reservists likely would be ordered to active duty.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration, preparing for an extended air
campaign now that three weeks of bombing has failed to halt the
Serb war on ethnic Albanians, also will seek emergency money from
Congress for the NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton Tuesday asked members of Congress to give the NATO
attack more time to smash Serb forces instead of pushing for
consideration of sending U.S. ground troops into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The extra air power likely would require calling up military
reservists, Bacon said, although he didn't know how many would be
needed or when it might happen.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred Air National Guard members already are
participating as volunteers in addition to about 22,000
active-duty U.S. forces involved in NATO operations.
</P>
<P>
The biggest recent mobilization of reserves was for the 1991
Gulf War, when about 230,000 from the Army, Air Force, Navy and
Marine Corps were called to active duty.
</P>
<P>
The Army also may need to mobilize National Guard and Reserve
members as part of Task Force Hawk, the contingent of Apache
attack helicopters and surface-to-surface missiles being assembled
in Albania to hit Serb tanks and armored forces in Kosovo.
</P>
