<HEADLINE> British Bomber Gets 224-Year Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The so-called Mardi Gra bomber,
Edgar Pearce, was jailed in London on Wednesday for 224 years for
his reign of terro and blackmail over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
But the 61-year-old man will actually only serve 21 years in
jail after Judge Michael Hyam at London's Old Bailey criminal
court ruled the sentences should run concurrently.
</P>
<P>
The judge said Pearce had been motivated by "greed and an
insatiable appetite for notoriety".
</P>
<P>
Pearce had admitted 23 offenses of blackmail, wounding,
possessing firearms and causing an explosion.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 bombs were left at Barclay's branches and
Sainsbury stores in London beginning in 1994. Several exploded but
no one was badly injured.
</P>
<P>
The devices were cobbled together from shotgun cartridges,
rifle bullets, springs, metal tubes and timers. They were usually
concealed in books, magazines and video cassette boxes. All
carried the signature "Mardi Gra". 
</P>
</TEXT>
