<HEADLINE> WTO Members Miss Deadline to Agree on New Chief Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) failed again to decide who will lead the
organization into the new century after a last-minute meeting here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Trade officials said that delegations of WTO's 134 members
faced difficulties in choosing a new director-general from two
candidates by consensus.
</P>
<P>
"We have not yet reached the point where we could appoint the
next Director-Genreal today," said Ambassador Ali Said Mchumo,
Chairman of WTO' governing body, the General Council.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to miss the inevitable deadline of April 30,
1999 when the incumbent Director-General leaves office," he told
the ambassadors of the 134 WTO members at the General Council
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand has been in the lead since
WTO began to choose its new director-general in the fourth quarter
of 1998. The other candidate, Michael Moore of New Zealand, is
believed to have the support from the United States and majority
support from Latin America and much of the sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The WTO members have missed several deadlines before to agree
on their new leader.
</P>
<P>
The incumbent WTO director-general, Renato Ruggiero, has said
that he would leave his post on April 30 at the end of a four-year
term in office. 
</P>
