<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Russian Officials Discuss Strategic Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Russian officials
discussed global strategic stability here Wednesday, especially
the issues relating to the Russian-U.S. Treaty on the Limitation
of Anti-Ballistic Missile System (ABM).
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Chinese Assistant Foreign Minister Wang
Guangya and Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Georgi Mamedov
stressed that it is of vital importance for all the parties
concerned to observe the treaty, which was signed on May 26, 1972
in Moscow by Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev and U.S. President
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
The two officials noted that the U.S. plan to develop anti-
missile systems contravenes the basic obligations specified by the
treaty, constitutes a new factor destabilizing the world situation,
provides an excuse for resuming arms race, and creates new
obstacles to the process of disarmament.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the officials said that the U.S. plan poses a
serious threat to the ABM treaty and that both China and Russia
are deeply concerned about the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
