<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Calls Indian Diplomat for Another Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday again called
the top Indian diplomat here to the Foreign Office and informed
him about the possible test-firing of a Shaheen missile, informed
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Acting High Commissioner Sharat Sabrawal was informed in
line with the Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) signed by Pakistan
and India foreign secretaries in Lahore at the conclusion of the
Indo-Pak Summit on February 21.
</P>
<P>
The MoU obliges the two countries to notify the other in
advance of the planned ballistic missile flight tests and a
bilateral agreement in this regard is under construction.
</P>
<P>
Shaheen, named after a bird which was often cited by great
Pakistani poet Alama Iqbal as a symbol of bravery, is another
series of Pakistan's guided missiles besides Ghauri.
</P>
<P>
Shabrawal was also invited to the Foreign Office on Tuesday
where he was informed about Pakistan's planned Ghauri-II missile
test-firing.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan test-fired the medium-range ballistic missile, which
is said to have a maximum range of 2,300 kilometers, on Wednesday
morning, with many people speculating upon more possible tests.
</P>
<P>
The tests are obviously a tit-for-tat response to India's
test-firing of its Agni-II missile last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
India successfully conducted a flight test of Agni-II, an
intermediate-range ballistic missile with a planned range of
around 2,200 kilometers, on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
India said Sunday that it had informed Pakistan's High
Commissioner in New Delhi Ashraf Jehangir Qazi prior to the
test-firing of its Agni-II missile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
