<HEADLINE> S. Africans Travelling Abroad to Be Able to Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Independent
Electoral Commission (IEC) Wednesday announced that voters, if out
of the country on June 2, will be able to vote provided that they
have already registered.
</P>
<P>
The IEC hopes that the move would reduce the number of court
cases against it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Nelson Mandela Wednesday signed the
proclamation confirming June 2 as the election date.
</P>
<P>
The IEC's concession, however, was not enough to stop the New
National Party and the Federal Alliance (FA) to continue their
court cases against the IEC.
</P>
<P>
The two parties want South Africans who are living abroad to be
able to vote as well. The majority of those people had not been
able to add their names to the voters' roll during the
registration period from November last year to March this year.
</P>
<P>
The legal challenges came after the Constitutional Court ruled
that prisoners would be able to vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
