<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Prices Lower With Inventory Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices fell Wednesday as
data on U.S. and European petroleum inventories proved less
supportive to the market than expected.
</P>
<P>
Benchmark Brent blend crude oil last closed 28 cents lower at
14.92 dollars a barrel in London.
</P>
<P>
Weekly figures from the American Petroleum Institute (API)
showed a rise in U.S. inventories of gasoline, diesel and heating
oil and higher crude stocks.
</P>
<P>
The API report followed data Tuesday from 16 European nations
showing crude stocks rose 3.8 percent or 17 million barrels from
February to 466 million barrels. Europe's year-on-year surplus of
crude stocks rose to 60 million barrels at the end of March from
50 million barrels at the end of February.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said a rise in exports from Russia in recent weeks
might be to blame with sales from former Soviet territories
running at post-Soviet record highs, according to a Reuters
report.
</P>
<P>
The International Energy Agency said last Friday that March
exports from the territories were estimated at 3.3 million barrels
a day despite Russia's pledge to OPEC that it would cut supplies.
</P>
<P>
Russia's rouble devaluation last year encouraged crude
producers and refiners to maximize export sales while domestic
Russian demand is still waning because of economic collapse,
Reuters said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
