<HEADLINE> Greece Urges Yugoslavia to Release Captured Australians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Greece Wednesday urged Belgrade to
release the two Australians now facing espionage charges in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
While recognizing the seriousness of the charges filed against
the two Australian aid workers and the conflict in which
Yugoslavia found itself, Greece respectfully encouraged Yugoslavia
to allow Australian Consular access to the workers and to consider
releasing the two as a humanitarian gesture, said a Greek Foreign
Ministry statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came following Mike Wran, leader of the South
Australian Labor Party, wrote to Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis asking him to intercede with Belgrade to release the two
men, Steve Pratt and Peter Wallace, both were charged of
intelligence gathering activities for the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Greece has voiced its opposition to the military actions by
NATO against Yugoslavia, and hoped to play a role of mediation
between Belgrade and NATO. 
</P>
