<HEADLINE> Blair, Ahern to Meet on N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The British and Irish prime
ministers will hold urgent talks in London Thursday to try to
break a stalemate over guerrilla disarmament which is paralyzing
Northern Ireland's peace process.
</P>
<P>
A senior politician in Northern Ireland made the announcement
Wednesday after two days of talks between local Protestant and
Roman Catholic politicians failed to make headway, according to a
Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
The parties were discussing a blueprint for progress issued by
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair when the last round of talks adjourned on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Rejected by the Irish Republican Army (IRA), its Sinn Fein
political wing and their hardline Protestant rivals, the paper's
survival seems in doubt, at least in its present form, Reuters
said.
</P>
<P>
Irish Deputy Foreign Minister Liz O'Donnell was quoted as
saying that progress would not be made on the basis of the
Hillsborough Declaration alone.
</P>
<P>
An Irish government briefing paper shown to reporters said
there was no consensus on the declaration.
</P>
<P>
"We have serious difficulties in moving forward to the
establishment of the institutions in the immediate future. This is
undoubtedly a disappointment and a setback," it said.
</P>
<P>
The shift in venue for Blair and Ahern, who had been expected
in Belfast Thursday, was further proof that no early breakthrough
was expected in the row between Catholic-backed Sinn Fein and
Protestant Ulster Unionists led by David Trimble. 
</P>
</TEXT>
