<HEADLINE> U.S. Gives $39m to Kenyan Blast Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States government gave
a 39 million U.S. dollars aid to the Kenyan government Wednesday
to reimburse the survivors of the August 7 bomb blast in the
Kenyan capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador Prudence Bushnell and Kenya Finance Minister
Francis Masakhalia signed the latest deal on behalf of the two
governments.
</P>
<P>
Masakhalia noted that while Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi's
earlier appeal for help had received a favorable response from
the international community, meeting the victims' long-term needs
still required a more coordinated approach.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the Kenyan government's distaste for
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Bushnell said the money would be used to provide medical,
social service and rehabilitation assistance to bomb survivors and
their families and to help the owners of businesses who suffered
economic losses in the terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
Bushnell hoped that the package, though inadequate compared to
the massive losses incurred, would go a long way to "erase pain
and ease anger" of the victims.
</P>
<P>
She said that the aid would improve Kenya's
disaster-preparedness through training and the establishment of
blood banks. 
</P>
