<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Winds Up U.S. Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOSTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
Wednesday afternoon concluded his eight-day official visit to the
United States, which Zhu described as "very constructive and
fruitful."
</P>
<P>
Before his departure from Boston, the last stop of his U.S.
tour, Zhu was present at a luncheon given in his honor by the
China Forum, a collaboration of Boston-area organizations that
sponsors an ongoing series of discussions for the region's
business community on issues relating to doing business in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier was given a standing ovation when he was
stepping to the podium in the banquet hall, which was decorated by
huge Chinese and U.S. national flags. His speech was frequently
punctuated by applause and his humorous remarks aroused pleasant
laughters from his audience of some 500 American business leaders,
academic leaders and members of the Chinese community in Boston
and the State of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu said that he and the Chinese government delegation
were warmly received in his visit to Los Angeles, Washington D.C.,
Denver, Chicago, New York and Boston. He voiced his heartfelt
thanks to the U.S. government and the American people as a whole
for their hospitality and friendship.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who started his official visit on April 6 at the
invitation of U.S. President Bill Clinton, is the first Chinese
premier to visit the country in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Premier Zhu made extensive contacts with
American business leaders, government officials and
representatives of U.S. commercial and financial circles.
</P>
<P>
"My talks with them are very friendly, frank, constructive and
fruitful," he said. "Therefore, I would like to convey my
heartfelt thanks to President Clinton, the U.S. government and the
American people."
</P>
<P>
In return, both Governor Paul Cellucci of the State of
Massachusetts and Thomas Menino, mayor of Boston, said that the
United States also benefits from advancing its friendship and
cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Over recent years, Massachusetts has made rapid progress in
developing economic and trade cooperation with China, thus
creating many job opportunities for the people in the state,
Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
The American people were profoundly impressed by the Chinese
premier during his visit, Menino said. He voiced his hope to see
closer ties of friendship and cooperation between the City of
Boston and China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier fielded all the questions from his audience
after his speech. In answering a question, Zhu said that China
welcomes investment from American businesses.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Boston, Zhu also met with representatives of
the local Chinese community.
</P>
<P>
Zhu left here for Ottawa to kick off his official visit to
Canada at the invitation of Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
</TEXT>
