<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Europe's Main Stock Markets End in Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON April 14 (Xinhua) - Europe's major stock markets closed
mostly lower Wednesday as a shortage of corporate news and an
uninspiring start on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The London stock market was unable to repeat Tuesday's record
close and ended down 19.5 points, or 0.3 percent, at 6493.6.
</P>
<P>
It was a quiet day on the corporate news front. One analyst
said: "I see the FTSE 100 going a bit lower. The market is poised
for a bit of profit taking."
</P>
<P>
Imperial Chemical Industries was the biggest gainer among the
UK's largest stocks. ICI shares ended up 47p at 635p on reports
that it is close to selling key assets to a US based company.
</P>
<P>
Smaller stock fared better than the UK's largest companies. The
FTSE 250 index closed 45.1 points higher at 5637.5.
</P>
<P>
Investors are shifting from some of the highly rated blue chip
stocks into second liners, said a trader at a UK brokerage.
</P>
<P>
Negative news from two index heavyweights prevented Germany's
electronically-traded Xetra Dax from building a head of steam at
the session.
</P>
<P>
The leading index finished down 0.74 percent, or 38.46 points,
at 5186.76 points, pressured by its most heavily traded stock
DaimlerChrylser.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, shares perked up to finish off their lows for the day
after a better than expected early performance on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Cac 40 index of leading shares was down 18 points at 4349
having earlier been as low as 4362. volume for the day was 2.57
billion euros. 
