<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Meeting to Be Held for G. Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A donors conference is to be held
on April 20 in New York to raise funds for the deployment of 850
additional troops in Guinea Bissau before legislative and
presidential elections, an official of the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Adrienne Diop, ECOWAS director of information, said here that
friends of Guinea Bissau are expected to contribute an amount for
the deployment of the troops to be contributed by countries with
troops in that country.
</P>
<P>
Benin Republic, Gambia and Togo deployed 712 troops already in
the country under the November peace deal in Abuja with the
assistance of France in February this year.
</P>
<P>
The troops are to be deployed along the border with Senegal,
which accused elements of the country's military of supporting
rebels in its Casamance region as well as used to monitor the
elections.
</P>
<P>
The elections are meant to produce a new national assembly and
a replacement for President Joao Vieira, one of the conditions
listed by the rebels before their cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The troops replaced the 3,000 Senegalese and Guinean soldiers
who entered the country at the invitation of President Vieira
after the June 7 rebellion by sacked army chief General Ansumane
Mane.
</P>
<P>
The rebellion was sparked after General Mane was sacked by the
president for being behind the support for the Casamance rebels.
</P>
<P>
Diop said the donors conference was being held to ensure the
timely deployment of the additional troops since those on the
ground were not adequate to monitor the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
