<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activists Protest Confiscation of Palestinian Residency Status in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of Palestinian and Israeli
civil rights activists, joined by legislators from both sides,
protested Wednesday against what they called Israel's discriminatory
policy of confiscating residency status of Palestinians in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Confined at a park outside the Old City by barriers set up by
Israeli police, the protesters chanted slogans and waved stickers
calling for an immediate end to a three-year-old Israeli policy under
which 2,083 Palestinian families have been stripped of their residency
status in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
They said this "discriminatory and unjust" policy violated
the international law and is "nothing less than a policy of ethnic
cleansing."
</P>
<P>
The demonstration was held to put pressure on Israel's High Court
of Justice as it prepares to hear next week a petition filed by
lawyers and civil rights groups about one year ago questioning the
legality of Jerusalem ID card confiscation.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli laws and regulations, Palestinian residents in East
Jerusalem, which was seized by Israel from Jordan in the 1967 Middle
East War, can retain their permanent residency status as long as they
did not live outside the city for more than seven years and returned
periodically.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli Interior Ministry in 1996 adopted a new policy
under which the residency status of Palestinians born in East
Jerusalem but living abroad or in the city's suburb was subject to
confiscation because the "center of life" of these people had been
changed.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the so-called "center of life" policy
has lead to a dramatic 600 percent increase in the number of ID card
confiscation cases.
</P>
<P>
During this period, about 8,332 Palestinian individuals have lost
their rights to live in East Jerusalem and as a result, the rights to
welfare and social security. Some of them were forced to move out of
the city because it was too hard for them to get permits from the
Israeli authority to build new houses there to accommodate the
expansion of their family.
</P>
<P>
They said the policy was discriminatory against the 215,000
Palestinian residents in East Jerusalem because Jewish residents there
can retain their permanent residency status without restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The protesters raised a sticker depicting a forged ID Card of Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu with the red-colored word "expired" on it.
On top of the sticker was a line which said, "Bibi, you were abroad
for 12 years. Now it's your turn," referring to the fact that
Netanyahu had stayed in the United States for a dozen of years before
returning to Israel in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Several members of the Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC) and
the Israeli Parliament, or Knesset, took part in the demonstration to
show their support and solidarity for the Palestinians who have lost
their Jerusalem ID cards.
</P>
<P>
PLC member Hanan Ashrawi, former cabinet minister of the
Palestinian National Authority, said Jerusalem is the "heart of peace"
and Israel's discriminatory policy "will destroy any possibility of
peace."
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli-Palestinians accords, the status of Jerusalem
should be determined in the final-status talks, which have yet to
start. Before the talks end, both sides are banned from taking
unilateral actions to change the status quo of the city, including its
demographic structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Aid Agency Sends Water in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) has embarked on an emergency water trucking
operation in a bid to ease the plight of Somali nomads who are
suffering a severe water shortage, the ICRC Nairobi office said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In order to save lives, the ICRC has mobilized hundreds of
trucks carrying water to some 70, 000 of the most vulnerable
pastoralists in 205 locations in central Somalia, that are worst
hit by the draught.
</P>
<P>
Rains due in April were delayed in some regions of Somalia and
 traditional water storage holes have been depleted.
</P>
<P>
Already in early March, ICRC teams assessing the humanitarian
needs with local water authorities came across some dead animals.
This week ICRC Somali field officers will report the loss of
human lives.
</P>
<P>
If the rains do not come in the next few weeks, the situation
will become extremely alarming, said the ICRC head of delegation
in Nairobi, Michel Dufour.
</P>
<P>
Dufour said that people in central Somalia have been caught in
a vicious cycle that they cannot break on their own. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
