<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commuters Affected in Nationwide Bus Strike in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of
commuters throughout South Africa, including school children, have
been stranded due to the disruption of a nation-wide bus strike
which began in the morning.
</P>
<P>
People worst affected by the bus strike were those in areas
where there was no alternatives to bus transport, such as trains
or taxis, Labor Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
The bus strike started following a deadlock in wage
negotiations between four major transport unions and the South
African Bus Employers' Association (SABEA).
</P>
<P>
About 18,000 transport employees have been involved in the
countrywide strike, the South African Broadcasting Corporation
reported.
</P>
<P>
The workers are demanding an 11-percent wage increase, whereas
management is offering only six percent, the strike organizers
said.
</P>
<P>
The SABEA officials said they would not resume wage talks with
the striking workers until they agreed to compromise.
</P>
<P>
So far, the strike has not seriously affected municipal bus
services in the country, as the municipal drivers do not belong to
any of the four unions involved in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Bus transport in and around Durban, the biggest port city in
South Africa, was reportedly operating normally and the Durban
city police had received no reports of any problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
