<HEADLINE> Drought Threatens Plants At China's Horticulture Exposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Fire engines have been racing
around the streets of Kunming in southwest China's Yunnan Province
recently, but they're not busy putting out fires - they're trying
to save hundreds of thousands of flowers and trees from 94
countries and international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Kunming is where the International Horticulture Exposition is
expected to open on May 1, but it has been suffering from a
drought since January. Temperatures have climbed to near 30
degrees centigrade in the daytime, making the situation worse.
</P>
<P>
Normally, Kunming has 40 mm of rainfall in April, but this year,
the forecast is for 15 mm, according to a provincial government
official. And the sprayers that are supposed to alleviate the
problems don't work well at the exhibition site because of a lack
of water pressure, even though there are three ponds with nearly
12,000 cu.m. in all nearby. 
</P>
