<HEADLINE> Annan Says UN Mission in Prevlaka Peninsula Helps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Thursday urged Croatia and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia to show restraint and maintain their resolve to
negotiate constructively towards a peaceful resolution of their
dispute over the Prevlaka peninsula.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report on the work of the United Nations Mission
of Observers in Prevlaka (UNMOP), Annan said the mission's
presence on the ground had played a key role in creating an
environment for a negotiated settlement, and during the present
time, it had also helped minimize tensions that could develop as a
result of events in the region.
</P>
<P>
Annan said it was extremely disappointing that substantial
progress had not been made even though six months had elapsed
since negotiations were initiated and four rounds of talks have
taken place.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief noted the current events in the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia should not be used by one party or the other to
achieve an objection outside the framework of bilateral
negotiations as specified in their Agreement on Normalization of
Relations.
</P>
<P>
UNMOP monitors the demilitarization of the Prevlaka peninsula
and neighboring areas in Croatia and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia. The mission, which consists of 27 military
observers, conducts vehicle and foot patrols on both sides of
the border and also meets regularly with local authorities to
reduce tensions, improve safety and security, and promote
confidence between the parties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
