<HEADLINE> U.S. Jobless Claims Rise to 3-Month High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The number of Americans filing
applications for unemployment checks jumped last week, for the
second consecutive week, to the highest level in three months, the
Labor Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A seasonally adjusted 316,000 unemployed people claimed
benefits, the highest since mid January and up from 302,000 the
week before, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Through nine weeks during late January, February and March, the
number of initial claims had hovered just under 300,000, the
longest stretch below that threshold since 1973.
</P>
<P>
The latest increase wasn't expected by analysts, but weekly
claims data are volatile and it's too soon to tell if it presages
any weakening in the very strong labor market, which in March cut
the nation's unemployment rate to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
A four-week moving average of claims, which evens out weekly
fluctuations, rose by 4,250 to 300,500. 
</P>
</TEXT>
