<HEADLINE> Finland New Cabinet Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A new five-party coalition
government headed by a social democrat Paavo Lipponen was
inaugurated Wednesday after nomination by President Martti
Ahitsaari.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet, composed of the Finnish Social Democratic
Party, National Coalition Party, Left-wing Alliance, Swedish
People's Party and Green League, has the same political foundation
as the last one and is called Lipponen's second government.
</P>
<P>
The five parties in the ruling coalition pocket 140 seats in
the 200-seat parliament and thus form a majority government.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the 18-member cabinet are new faces and eight are
female ministers. Prime Minister Lipponen, Foreign Minister Tarja
Halonen, Finance Minister Sauli Niinistoe and Agriculture Minister
Kalevi Hemilae retain their posts.
</P>
<P>
The newly elected ones include Defense Minister Jan-Erik
Enestam, Minister of Trade and Industry Kimmo Sasi, Interior
Minister Kari Hakamies, Education Minister Maija Rask, Minister of
Social and Health Affairs Satu Hassi.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet said in a platform that Finland would continue
to pursue the current diplomatic and security policies, stick to
military non-alliance and reliable defense and take an active part
in the European integration process.
</P>
<P>
It also promised that the country would strengthern its
cooperation with other northern European nations and the three
Baltic nations and work to improve the relations between the
European Union and Russia.
</P>
<P>
As for domestic policies, the new government vowed to further
improve employment, continue stringent economic policies and
reform taxation and welfare systems in a bid to guarantee a steady
economic growth and a balance in revenues and expenditures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
