<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Urges New Delhi to Return to Jute Organization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh on Thursday requested
India to reconsider its decision of pulling out the International
Jute Organization (IJO).
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria made the appeal to India,
once an important member of the Dhaka-based organization, at the
inaugural session of a three-day "Jute Investors' Forum," jointly
organized by the Ministry of Jute, the Board of Investment, the
IJO and others.
</P>
<P>
India withdrew its membership from the IJO in January this
year. The IJO, an inter-governmental agency with 26 member states,
was established in 1984 to implement the provisions of the 1982
International Agreement on Jute and Jute Products.
</P>
<P>
Believing that jute has the economic strength to survive the
tough competition with synthetics, the finance minister stressed
the need for more research and timely entrepreneurial initiatives
to make jute viable and regain its lost glory.
</P>
<P>
Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed said the
ministries of jute and commerce and industries would launch a
comprehensive plan of action soon to produce and export more jute,
calling on jute producing countries to work together to invigorate
the struggling jute industry.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to give cash incentive to exporters
of jute and jute goods to help strengthen the jute economy, but
the jute industry can survive and regain its lost glory only
through diversification of products, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's raw jute export has fallen sharply in both volume
and value in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The export of raw jute fell by more than 50 percent during the
first half of the current fiscal year (July 1998-June 1999) to
about 613,000 bales from 1.277 million bales in the corresponding
period of the previous fiscal, reports said.
</P>
<P>
And the export earnings from the jute sector also declined by
over 50 percent, coming down to about 1.13 billion taka (about
23.3 million U.S. dollars) in the period from nearly 2.37 billion
taka (about 48.9 million dollars) in the same period of the last
fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
