<HEADLINE> Philippines' Employment Rises by 2.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Labor Secretary
Bienvenido Laguesma said Thursday that results of the January 1999
Labor Force Survey indicate some improvements in employment, a
sign that some sectors of the economy are on the road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
According to Laguesma, data from the Department of Labor and
Employment's (DOLE) Bureau of Labor and Employment Statistics
(BLES) showed a 2.4-percent growth in the number of employed
persons in January 1999 compared with the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that employed persons rose from 27.69 million
in January 1998 to 28.37 million in January 1999. This means that
about 679,000 more workers were employed in the first month of
this year compared with a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The increase in employment is about twice the 357,000
employment increment registered in the same month last year,
Laguesma said.
</P>
<P>
The labor secretary said the higher employment growth could be
attributed to improvements in the agricultural and financial
sectors which are badly hit by a prolonged drought and the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, DOLE noted a slight increase in unemployment of 9
percent in January 1999 from 8.4 percent in January 1998. This was
due partly to higher labor force participation rates observed
among women, young and urban workers for the first quarter this
year.
</P>
<P>
The higher participation rates could mean that more persons are
finding the need to work or more of them have become more
optimistic that they could now get a job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
