<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Home Secretary Blocks Freedom for Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
British Home Secretary Jack Straw has ruled that the legal
action, extradition hearing against the retired general, should go
ahead.
</P>
<P>
Straw said he made the decision with an "open mind" and that
the Spanish request was well founded.
</P>
<P>
The Home Secretary, who had once ruled late last year that the
extradition hearing should go ahead, has been asked to reconsider
his approval by the Lords after they adjudged that Pinochet should
not take responsibilities to all the crimes the Spanish judge
charged on him.
</P>
<P>
Since that rule effectively reduced 32 draft charges against
Pinochet to three, the Law Lords also asked Straw to review his
December's ruling that extradition proceeding could begin.
</P>
<P>
Most of Spain's allegations were from the earlier part of
Pinochet's 1973-1990 rule.
</P>
<P>
Straw's decision on Thursday did not mean extradition hearings
will start right away or they would result in his extradition.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet's lawyers could force a delay by appealing Straw's new
ruling to London's High Court.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was house arrested last October in a London's hospital
where he was recovering from a back surgery. A Spanish judge
accused him of being responsible for the deaths and disappearances
of 3,000 people during his reign, and wanted him be extradited to
Spain to face trials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
