<HEADLINE> Israeli Shas Party Leader Sentenced for Graft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Aryeh Deri, leader of Israel's
powerful rightwing Shas Party, Thursday was sentenced to four years in
prison by Jerusalem District Court for bribe-taking.
</P>
<P>
Deri was also fined 250,000 shekels (about 60,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Deri, a close associate of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, was
convicted of graft, fraud and breaching the public trust by Jerusalem
District Court last month.
</P>
<P>
The court said that Deri took 155,000 dollars in bribes in
return for using his senior position in the Interior Ministry in the
late 1980s to provide some organizations with special treatment and
government funding.
</P>
<P>
Judge Yaacov Tzemach said Thursday that the tough sentence
reflected the gravity of the crime.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was not a one-time mistake made by Deri, noting
that taking bribe has been part of his life style during a period of
over five years.
</P>
<P>
Tzemach stressed that Deri was the first sitting minister in
Israel who took bribes, and the bribe-taking "presented an extreme
danger to the nation and the people."
</P>
<P>
Deri has the right to appeal to the High Court within 45 days
following the sentencing. His attorney asked the court to delay
implementing the sentence until the High Court rules on the appeal.
</P>
<P>
But the prosecutor insisted that Deri be jailed immediately. The
court is now discussing the delay.
</P>
<P>
Shas Party, which currently has 10 seats in the 120-member Knesset
(parliament), is made up of Jews with Middle Eastern origin.
</P>
<P>
Followers of Shas regarded the conviction as a ruling against the
whole party, and have held several demonstrations over the last
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
Since it is only about one month before the general elections in
May, Deri's sentence is likely to raise tensions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local political analysts said that the conviction of
Deri could rally Shas supporters to the polls and help the
right-wing Netanyahu in the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
