<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cambodia Celebrates First Peaceful New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 15 (Xinhua) -- With the Khmer New Year coming
in, you can feel the festivity everywhere in Cambodia which is
celebrating the first peaceful New Year in nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
All over Phnom Penh, people are celebrating and greeting the
Year of the Rabbit which began Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
People, old and young, are wearing their best colorful
traditional clothes. Many people are busy with shopping in the
markets which have an ample supply of commodities. And many
families drove a long way to visit historic sites or have an
excursion.
</P>
<P>
At night, young people gather in circles in the streets or in
parks for a mixture of traditional dance and pop music.
</P>
<P>
The government and authorities concerned also organized varied
and colorful festival activities, such as movies, traditional
dance performance and traditional Khmer games.
</P>
<P>
Among the Buddhist ceremonies performed is the mountain of
sand, meant to show that each mountain is composed of individual
grains of sand or dirt and so life can be changed little by
little. Another popular ceremony is the watering of the Buddha, in
which people throw water on a Buddha statue.
</P>
<P>
Many families invited monks to perform ceremonies to rid their
houses of negative spirits left over from the old year.
</P>
<P>
People have all the reason to celebrate this year. Just as a
foreigner who has been here for seven years noted that it is the
first year when a really good feeling exists around town.
Everybody knows there is no trouble out there.
</P>
<P>
It is true that for the first time in nearly 30 years, Cambodia
finally enjoys a true, comprehensive peace. There is no Khmer
Rouge fighting force in the jungle and a new coalition government
was formed with former warring factions now working together.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations represent a contrast to those of last New
Year, which came immediately after the return of Prince Norodom
Ranariddh on March 30, who left the country following the July
1997 factional fighting. Tensions were high, and some feared new
violence would erupt. At the same time, Royal Cambodian Armed
Forces (RCAF) were battling Khmer Rouge near Anlong Veng.
</P>
<P>
And New Year's Day in 1997 came less than three weeks after
four grenades exploded outside the National Assembly, shattering
the dream of stability. At least 17 people were killed and more
than 100 injured. Weeks later the fragile coalition government
fell apart and factions took up arms against each other.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation is totally different this year. All the
people seem to be happy together. Some boys and girls, playing
games at park, said, "Cambodia suffered too much for too long a
time, but from now on we'll have no more fighting and we will live
in peace, so we should take the chance to enjoy ourselves."
</P>
<P>
In order to let the people have a peaceful and happy New Year,
police and military police increased their patrol along the
streets day and night.
</P>
<P>
Senate President Chea Sim, National Assembly President Prince
Norodom Ranariddh and Prime Minister Hun Sen all gave to the
people their New Year blessing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hun Sen said, "With the 21st century coming,
Cambodia already has achieved complete peace. And this is the good
fortune for our people as after the July 26 elections we have
ended the political and military organization of the Khmer Rouge."
</P>
<P>
They all appealed to the whole country to make every effort to
achieve prosperity and development in Cambodia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
