<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Proposes Three-Stage Peace Plan for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
has outlined a three-stage peace plan for settling the Kosovo
crisis, which called for a simultaneous stop of NATO bombardment
and deployment of peace-keepers from neutral nations.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma's plan appeared to be a compromise taking into account
both NATO and Yugoslav demands, said a report carried by the
government newspaper Uriadovyi Kur'er on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the interview with the newspaper, Kuchma said the first
stage involves a simultaneous cease-fire by Yugoslav forces in the
Kosovo province, by Albanian separatists and by NATO units bombing
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Peace-keepers acting under the auspices of the United Nations
or the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe would
then enter Kosovo simultaneously with a Yugoslav withdrawal, and
provide for the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
The second stage involves the return and resettlement of
refugees and the third -- a peace conference in a neutral capital.
In the meantime, the United Nations, the Red Cross and other
international bodies would take care of the refugees in Yugoslavia
and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is prepared to participate in the peace-keeping
contingent, Kuchma said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the peace-keeping force must be acceptable for
all sides to the conflict and not be a NATO force, as earlier
proposed by the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said he was prepared to immediately start talks with
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and the leaders of Kosovo Albanians, send his Foreign
Minister Boris Tarasiuk to Belgrade or Washington or host peace
talks in the Ukrainian capital of Kiev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
