<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Says Missile Tests for Security Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan said Thursday that its
latest missile tests have been conducted basically for "a security
need and to maintain credible, efficacious and technically sound
deterrence."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here Thursday, Foreign Office
spokesman Tariq Altaf said the South Asian region is faced with "a
precariously instable situation."
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan must always remains, as it always does, mindful of
its security needs," he said, adding that "our security needs
require that we maintain a minimum, credible deterrence."
</P>
<P>
Altaf's remarks came after Pakistan launched a Shaheen-I
surface-to-surface ballistic missile Thursday one day after
Wednesday's test fire of Ghauri-II as a response to India's
test-fire of Agni-II last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We have to make sure that our deterrence is efficacious,
technically sound, dependable and credible," Altaf said.
</P>
<P>
"We conducted (missile) tests in view of our technical
requirements to maintain our minimum deterrence capability," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan is engaged in a dialogue process with
neighboring India. In this dialogue process and at the foreign
secretary-level meetings, Pakistan has already offered to enter
into "a strategic restraint regime for nuclear and conventional
stabilization."
</P>
<P>
"It is our earnest wish that the two countries should reach an
agreement on a restraint regime," said Altaf, adding that "this
restraint regime will promote peace and security in the region
along with resolution of disputes."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Pakistan's proposals for a strategic restraint
regime should be looked into even more seriously and more
urgently.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the Ghauri-II missile test,
conducted Wednesday, was in the range of around 1,160 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The maximum range of overland test within Pakistan's
territorial limits is around 1,500 kilometers, he said, adding
that the capability of Ghauri-II is higher and in the range of
2,000 to 2,300 kilometers depending on the weight of the payload.
</P>
<P>
Asked about more possible missile tests by Pakistan, Altaf
quoted a Foreign Office press release issued Thursday as saying
that "this test (of Shaheen-I Thursday) concludes, for now, the
series of SSM (surface-to-surface missile) flight tests involving
solid and liquid fuel rocket motor technologies, which started
yesterday."
</P>
<P>
Answering another question, the spokesman stressed that the
latest missile program is indigenous, and the successful tests are
the result of scientific research by Pakistan's scientists and
technicians.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the spirit of the memorandum of
understanding reached by Pakistan and India in February this year,
the Pakistani side had informed the Indian side about its missile
launching plan beforehand, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
