<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Demands Withdrawal of Eritrean Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government
spokesperson Selome Taddesse said Thursday that Eritrea must
formally agree "to withdraw from the Ethiopian territories it
currently occupies" before a ceasefire can take place.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Thursday afternoon on Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi's interview with Voice of America this week, the
spokesperson quoted him as saying that as soon as the Eritrean
government accedes to this requirement, a ceasefire can be
implemented, followed by demilitarization and demarcation of the
common border.
</P>
<P>
To date, said the statement, "Eritrea has only agreed to a
ceasefire without accepting the entire package deal."
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesperson, Prime Minister Meles stressed
that as soon as Eritrea formally signs a package deal that very
clearly indicates that they will withdraw from all Ethiopian
territories within a specified time frame, a ceasefire can take
place.
</P>
<P>
The statement quoted Meles as saying that "the Ethiopian
government does not accept new ceasefire proposals that are meant
simply to facilitate negotiations without including the key
element of Eritrean withdrawal."
</P>
<P>
"Only when the Asmara government agrees to this requirement, as
embodied in the Organization of African Unity (OAU) plan, can a
ceasefire be implemented, followed by peaceful negotiation of the
border issue," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Both Ethiopia and Eritrean have accepted the OAU framework
agreement which calls for both sides to pull back their troops and
allow intonational monitors into the disputed areas while a border
commission establishes a mutually recognized international
boundary.
</P>
<P>
The 11-month Ethio-Eritrean border dispute escalated into
fierce fighting in June 1998 and renewed in February and March
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
