<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clan Fighting Raging in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Clannish and political clashes
continued raging in southern Somalia, devastating the already poor
 humanitarian situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Somali extreme southern border with Kenya
indicated that there has been armed clashes between militiamen
form the Islamic fundamentalist group of Al-Itihad Al-Islam and
others loyal to General Mohamed Saeed Hirsi Morgan in Rascamboni
town on the border.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here in Mogadishu, four battle
wagons and nearly 100 heavily armed militiamen loyal to General
Morgan have attacked the Islamists militia bases in Rascamboni
town early Wednesday morning. The VHF radio reports said the
fighting has left over ten people dead and more than 20 others
wounded.
</P>
<P>
A VHF radio owner in the region told Xinhua that the
perpetrators of the attack have lost the battle but had managed to
escape with their battle wagons back to the port town of Kismaio,
500 km south of the capital, from where they had launched their
attack.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the attack is not officially known. However,
sources close to the militiamen of Colonel Ahmed Hashi said the
attack was meant to dislodge the Islamic fundamentalists
militiamen of Abdusalam Turki from the town.
</P>
<P>
The reason why General Morgan's men are trying to dislodge the
 fundamentalists from the region is also said to have related to
the killing of an American woman aid worker in the area about a
month ago. Even though the Al-Itihad men have denied the killing,
speculations are that Al- Itihad militiamen from the area have
killed her as she crossed the border to Somali side.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the armed confrontations between rival sides among
Somalis and those of the Ethiopian forces along the border of Gedo
region are seriously worsening the humanitarian situation by
creating new streams of internally displaced people.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of families who recently fled the towns of Bulo Hawo
and Dolow of Gedo region still remain stranded in the region
without food or shelter.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian crises are not confined to the border towns.
There are also serious reports of humanitarian difficulties in
other towns of the region. Yussuf Hassan Eyow, governor of the
region, said at least four people die everyday in Galhareri town
while three others also die in Dhusamareb due to water scarcity
and severe diarrhea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
