<HEADLINE> Swazi King Rules out Abolition of Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- King Mswati III of Swaziland
Thursday ruled out the abolition of the death penalty in the tiny
southern African country, saying the threat that necessitates
capital punishment in the country still exists.
</P>
<P>
Although no hangings have taken place in the country in the
past 18 years, the sentence has acted as an effective deterrent to
crime, South African Press Association quoted Mswati as saying in
Mbabane, the capital.
</P>
<P>
Serious crimes such as ritual killings would soar once the
death sentence is abolished, he said.
</P>
<P>
The country should concentrate more on fighting crime than
lobbying for the abolition of capital punishment, said the king.
</P>
<P>
While the death penalty still remains in place in Swaziland,
Mswati said this is cushioned by his prerogative of mercy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
