<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Resume Financial Aid to Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Donors have released a total of 36
million U.S. dollars to Zambia so far this year, the Bank of
Zambia said.
</P>
<P>
Kabinga Pande, spokesman of Zambia's central bank, said here
Wednesday that of the 36 million dollars, 22.4 million of which
was from the European Union and the remaining came from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia newspaper Thursday quoted the spokesman as
saying that the bank expects more inflows from other multilateral
and bilateral partners.
</P>
<P>
The donors withheld their promised balance-of-payment support
to Zambia last year because of the delayed privatization of the
country's copper mines.
</P>
<P>
IMF Executive Director Dinah Guti said when he visited Zambia
last year that the donors did not wish to see a large chunk of the
pledged aid go to a loss-making program like the Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM).
</P>
<P>
In December, 1998, Anglo-American Corporation and Zambia signed
a memorandum of understanding over the sale of ZCCM's Nchanga,
Nkana and Konkola mines, paving the way for the resumption of the
aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
