<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Tighten Control over Environmental Pollution by New Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts are to improve
the official assessment techniques for checking on the pollution a
new project can pose to the environment.
</P>
<P>
Wu Bo, head of the Division of Development Management and
Monitoring under the State Environmental Protection Administration
(SEPA), promised that the assessment system, one of the country's
three major environmental systems, will be strictly implemented
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The administration has revoked the licenses of two state-level
environmental inspection organizations, including the State
Environmental Analysis and Measuring Center, for providing wrong
results.
</P>
<P>
China has used the system since the 1970s. Projects failing to
meet certain standards for environmental protection cannot be
carried out according to state regulations.
</P>
<P>
"The system has played an important role in preventing the
emergence of new polluting sources," Wu said, adding that 95
percent of all the construction projects have been assessed as to
whether they would cause serious pollution before work begin.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the two revoked licenses, another eight
organizations including the China Architectural Research Institute,
have ordered to cease work for using unqualified personnel.
</P>
<P>
China currently has more than 260 organizations with state-
level licenses and nearly 6,000 people involved in the business.
</P>
<P>
Wu said, "The bulk of these organizations are running well and
have contributed greatly to pollution control. However, some
organizations have serious problems and even practice fraud in
assessment.
</P>
<P>
"The state will tighten control over these organizations and
will revoke the licenses of those that employ trickery."
</P>
<P>
The SEPA has promulgated a new regulation, withdrawing the
authority to issue licenses by the administration and making
higher demands on the assessment of personnel.
</P>
<P>
The administration has begun issuing new licenses according to
the new regulation and all the old ones will expire beginning from
January 1, 2000. Sources say that fewer new licenses will be
issued this time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
