<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wrap-up: FM Spokesman's Statement at Press Conference (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's
visit to the United States is constructive, fruitful and conducive
to furthering a sustained, healthy and steady progress of the
China-US relations, a foreign ministry spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a regular press conference, the spokesman, Sun Yuxi, said
that the official visit to the US by Premier Zhu at the invitation
of President Bill Clinton is another major event in the China-US
relations, following the successful exchange of visits by the
heads of state of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Premier Zhu had a wide-range and in-depth
exchange of views with President Clinton and other American
leaders on China-US relations and major international and regional
issues, and the two sides expressed their continued commitment to
build a constructive China-US strategic partnership, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the question of Taiwan, Sun said, Premier Zhu expounded
China's consistent position, and President Clinton reaffirmed the
US adherence to a one China and relevant commitments.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu and President Clinton issued a joint statement on
China's accession to the WTO, and the US side undertook to support
China's accession to the WTO in 1999. Premier Zhu also elaborated
on the principled position of the Chinese side on the Kosovo issue,
Sun said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Premier Zhu and Vice-President Gore co-chaired
the Second Session of the China-US Environment and Development
Forum, and the two sides also signed a series of agreements and
letters of intent on agriculture, civil aviation, customs, energy
and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu had extensive contacts with people from all walks
of life in the US, thus promoting the mutual understanding and
friendship between the Chinese and American people, he said.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question on China's reaction toward the recent
assassination of an Iranian army leader, Sun denied any knowledge
of the assassination, but reiterated that "China always opposes
international terrorism".
</P>
<P>
China also expresses its deep concern and regret over the
civilian casualties caused by NATO's air strikes against
Yugoslavia, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
China has always held that NATO should stop the air strikes in
order to avoid the situation there from being complicated and
deteriorated, and turn the Kosovo issue back to the track of
political settlement, Sun added.
</P>
<P>
On Pakistan's test-fire of a mid-range missile Wednesday, Sun
said that China hopes India and Pakistan to concretely observe the
United Nations Resolution No.1172 in a bid to ensure regional
peace and stability in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's missile launch came after the test-launching of a
mid-range missile by India on April 11, and "the situation is
detrimental to the peace and stability in South Asia," he added.
</P>
<P>
All relevant sides are urged to take measures with responsible
attitude in order to prevent arms race acceleration in the region,
Sun said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
