<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Sentence for Buddha Statue Thief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A death sentence was handed down
today on a thief who stole and later, accidentally, destroyed
Beijing's oldest statue of Buddha.
</P>
<P>
Chen Mengxing, a farmer from north China's Hebei province, was
also found guilty of stealing another rare relic from a temple in
Shouyang County in Shanxi Province dating back somewhere in the
Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), according to the verdict handed down by
the Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court.
</P>
<P>
His accomplices Liu Xueru and Wang Liqiang were given life
imprisonment by the same court ruling.
</P>
<P>
The 165-cm-high stone Buddha statue, weighing two tons, dates
back to 499 A.D. and had been kept safe and intact in a house in
the village of Dong'erying in the western part of Beijing for the
past 1,500 years.
</P>
<P>
Because of its rare historical and aesthetic value, the local
government has listed the statue as a rare relic since 1957.
</P>
<P>
However, the house was not equipped with any automatic warning
device despite a fact that police had previously advised local
people to use better anti-theft measures after they decided to
open the house to the public.
</P>
<P>
On the night of March 25, 1998, the gang stole the statue but
it was badly damaged as they tried to move it. They later hid the
remains of the statue in the backyard of Liu Xueru's home.
</P>
<P>
The three were arrested last October. The shattered statue of
Buddha was later found and has been carefully repaired by a group
of experts organized by Beijing Cultural Relics Administration.
The repaired statue is said to have regained its past glamor and
is now safely located in the Beijing Carved Stone Art Museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
