<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Says to Observe Cease-fire Without </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has said that it was
prepared to observe a cease-fire in the northern border without
demanding prior withdrawal of the Eritrean troops.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with foreign media in Addis Ababa Wednesday,
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi said that "we are not saying
they have to withdraw first before there is a cease-fire."
</P>
<P>
Without a cease-fire, Eritrea cannot withdraw its troops, the
prime minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Meles said that Ethiopia's new position was part of a package
which would allow Ethiopia to honor a cease-fire if Eritrea would
promise to withdraw its troops from territories Ethiopia
administered along the 1,000- kilometer common border until last
May.
</P>
<P>
"If the Eritreans were to sign on the dotted line of package
that very clearly indicated that they would withdraw from our
territories in a certain specific time, as soon as they sign on
that package, on that dotted line, there is a cease-fire as far as
we are concerned," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ethiopian state-run media have not released any
information so far about the new government position on the
11-month border dispute with Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
And there was no immediate comment from the Eritrean side on
Ethiopia's new position on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both Ethiopia and Eritrean have accepted the framework
agreement put forward by the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
The proposals contained in the framework agreement call for both
sides to pull back their troops and allow international monitors
into the disputed areas while a border commission establishes a
mutually recognized international boundary.
</P>
<P>
An OAU team, which was scheduled to leave for Asmara Tuesday,
is expected to Eritrea later this week to continue its peace
mission there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan Tuesday announced
that he would send his special envoy for Africa, Mohamed Sahnoun,
back to the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Tuesday also made a new call for an
immediate halt to the fighting between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
