<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Offers Support to China's Access to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The US aircraft manufacturer
Boeing said today that it has intensified its efforts to convince
the US Congress and the Clinton Administration to support China's
admission to World Trade Organization (WTO) and granting China
permanent extension of Most Favored Nation (MFN) status.
</P>
<P>
Ray Bracy, President of Boeing China Inc., today disclosed that
Philip M. Condit, chairman of the Business Round Table and
chairman and CEO of Boeing, recently wrote to President Clinton
and said, "It is now extremely important for the Clinton
Administration to press forward to resolve the remaining US-China
trade issues so that we can achieve the important objective of WTO
membership for China. Congress also will need to extend permanent
normal trade status to China as WTO rules require."
</P>
<P>
In the past 20 years, China has been expanding 2.5 times faster
than the economies of North America and Europe and it is predicted
by Boeing to be the world's largest in the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Bracy said, "Obviously, with a population of more than 1.2
billion, there is substantial business opportunity over the long
term in China, however, instability in US-China trade relations is
one of the biggest hurdles American companies face when they come
to do business in China."
</P>
<P>
That is why the Boeing Company, as one of the leaders of the
American business community, was dedicated to the effort to
accelerate the development of Sino-US relations, added Bracy.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that Boeing had a China work team made up of 200
persons, who were engaged in explaining the necessity of
maintaining normalized trade relations with China through various
ways.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the team had contacted more than 3,000 suppliers
in the US to advocate the benefits of improved Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
Bracy pointed out that the admission for China in the WTO would
help bring China's trade regime into compliance with international
norms, improve market access for foreign investments and help
China continue the economic reform.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
