<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia to Develop Its Own Diamond Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Namibia is planning to open
up its diamond trade, thus ending the 50-year monopoly of rough
diamond by foreign developers and traders, the Business Day
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Namibia's Standing Parliamentary Committee on Natural Resources
 reportedly submitted a report to the National Assembly early this
week, recommending that the diamond trade be deregulated and
decriminalized by the new Diamond Act.
</P>
<P>
The committee said the diamond trade was over-regulated and
overprotected, and ran contrary to stated government policy of
economic empowerment.
</P>
<P>
It recommended that Mines and Energy Minister Andima Toiva ya
Toiva be allowed to license diamond dealers to trade in uncut and
unpolished diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The committee recommended that the new law should apply to
Namibia's 200- kilometer exclusive economic zone, which would
bring the country's lucrative offshore diamond deposits under
direct state control.
</P>
<P>
It would also provide for the licensing of independent diamond
traders, as well as for the setting up of independent cutting and
polishing enterprises, a long cherished goal of the Namibian
government.
</P>
<P>
The bill tabled by the committee could be passed into law
before the end of the year, sources of parliament said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Namibia produced 1.3 million carats of diamonds. It
was estimated that Namibia's diamond output this year will come to
1.2 million carats.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian diamond trade has been monopolized by the South
African diamond giant De Beers and its London-based Central
Selling Organization.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian diamonds accounted for 10 percent of the total
sales of De Beers' selling branch in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
