<HEADLINE> Indian Parliament Debates on Motion of Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Lower House of the Indian
Parliament began debating on a motion moved by Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee to seek a vote of confidence for his government
here Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The crucial voting on the motion of confidence in the
13-month-old Vajpayee government will take place at noon on
Saturday after a reply to the debate by the prime minister,
parliament sources said here.
</P>
<P>
Initiating the debate, leader of the opposition in the house
Sharad Pawar made a severe attack on the Vajpayee government,
saying it had no achievement to its credit in its 13-month tenure
and lost the right to remain in office even for a minute.
</P>
<P>
He said the Vajpayee administration became a minority
government after All-India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam
(AIADMK), one of its major allies, withdrew its support to the
government on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The economic situation had worsened, industrial production
slowed down and there was an increase in unemployment and poverty,
he charged.
</P>
<P>
Questioning the timing of test-firing Agni-11 ballistic missile
last Sunday, Pawar wondered whether the step was conducive to the
improvement of relations with Pakistan. It could trigger an arms
race in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties were determined to vote out the Bharatiya
Janata Party (BJP)-led coalition and give the country a strong
secular alternative which could take it to the 21st century, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Another opposition party leader Laloo Prasad Yadav in his
debate asked Vajpayee to submit his resignation to the president
before the voting takes place on the confidence motion. The prime
minister should realize that the "ground is slipping from under
his feet," he said.
</P>
<P>
Home Minister L. K. Advani in the debate accused Congress of
trying to push the country to another mid-term poll and cautioned
other parties and groups not to fall into its trap.
</P>
<P>
"Congress wants this government to go so that fresh elections
could be held. All should understand this and have a rethinking on
the whole issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized Left parties for joining hands with
Congress, saying it went against their ideology and election
manifestoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
