<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Plans to Maintain Ancient Temples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has planned to maintain 12
ancient temples in the area of Aswan, 700 kilometers south of Cairo,
the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of the rock-cut temples in southern Egypt will be
finished this year in three phases, Minister of Culture Farouk Hosni
said during a visit to Aswan last week.
</P>
<P>
Local companies will assume the maintenance work, which is
estimated to cost 45 million Egyptian pounds (13.24 million U.S.
dollars), Hosni said.
</P>
<P>
Areas surrounding the temples are also to be upgraded by installing
light and sound system and paving roads leading to the archaeological
sites, he added.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of the temples is part of a project to develop
tourism as well as economy in southern Egypt, the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
The temples include the Philae, Amada, Al Daka and Al Mahraka,
which date back to the Ptolemaic age about 300 BC, and Al Dor, Abu
Simble and Al Sobu, which belong to the 19th dynasty ruled by Ramsis
II (1223-1290 BC).
</P>
<P>
Some of the temples were rescued from the rising water of Lake
Nasser after the construction of the High Dam on the Nile, under a
campaign launched by the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization in the 1960s. The monuments were moved to higher
places for preservation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
