<HEADLINE> Benazir Bhutto Awarded Five Years' Imprisonment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's former prime
minister Benazir Bhutto and her spouse were disqualified for
public office and awarded five years' imprisonment on Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The chairwoman of the Pakistan People's Party (PPP), the
largest opposition, and sitting senator, was also fined 8.6
million U.S. dollars for a corruption prosecution by Rawalpindi
Ehtesab (Accountability) bench of the Lahore High Court.
</P>
<P>
Her spouse Asif Zardari, former minister of investment in
Bhutto's cabinet and chairman of Central Board of Revenue, was
involved in the same case.
</P>
<P>
A short order was announced by the Ehtesab Bench that both the
accused persons got illegal gratification from the SGS and
Cotecna, both Swiss companies, against the award of contract for
customs evaluation.
</P>
<P>
The court in its short order observed that the prosecution has
succeeded in proving the case against the couple.
</P>
<P>
It further observed that the commission appointed by the court
to verify the validity of the documents from Swiss Authorities has
also confirmed that the documents provided by the prosecution were
valid and authenticated documents.
</P>
<P>
Bhutto's defending counsel Abdul Hafeez Pirzada, however, said
the decision of awarding contract to the two Swiss companies were
taken by the cabinet committee and the collective responsibility
lies in the cabinet though the prime minister was the first among
the equals.
</P>
<P>
Bhutto's PPP government was dismissed by the then president
Farooq Leghari in November 1996 and Nawaz Sharif won the following
general election to form the current Pakistan Muslim League
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
