<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Export Trade Fair Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The 85th China Export Commodity
Trade Fair, one of the country's most important annual occasions
for promoting exports, opened here today.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 64,000 business people from 177 countries and
regions are expected to attend the 15-day fair, which features
exhibits of domestic products ranging from textiles, light
industrial handicraft articles, machinery, and chemicals to
medicines, health care, food, and animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
This year's fair is the first after establishing a website on
the Internet, on which people can obtain information on exhibiting
companies and products.
</P>
<P>
No effort has been spared in the promotion of exports at the
fair, as restrictions on the transaction volume of high-tech
machinery producers have been lifted, and more overseas-invested
companies are being allowed to participate.
</P>
<P>
A number of private firms that have been given export rights
this year will be striking a pose at the fair, while some older
foreign trade companies have now disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Trade Fair has been held twice a year since 1957.
Its annual transactions normally account for 30 percent of the
country's total export volume, and some 21.2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of trade was accomplished at last year's two sessions.
</P>
<P>
The number of overseas buyers at the fair increase by about 10,
000 every two years on average. At the autumn fair last year,
contracts made with companies from the European Union accounted
for 31 percent of the total, and those with United States
companies amounted to 16 percent. Business with the countries of
Latin America and Africa also increased by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China's exports are facing mounting difficulties due
to a waning international market and Asia's financial crisis.
Foreign trade rose 0.3 percent in the first quarter, about the
same quarterly growth as last year, reaching 70 billion U.S.
dollars, with exports falling 7.9 percent to 37 billion U.S
dollars, according to Customs figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
