<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legal Service Hotline Popular in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Justice plans
to make a hotline service available nationwide within two years in
a bid to provide more general legal aid.
</P>
<P>
The hotline has already become functional in 730 counties, 24
percent of the total, since it was first set up by Dongming
County's justice bureau in east China's Shandong Province in March,
last year.
</P>
<P>
Dialing the unified number "148", ordinary people can ask local
justice authorities to provide legal consultation, lawyers,
notarization and other kinds of free or paid services, said an
official at the ministry's department of grassroots work.
</P>
<P>
More than 140,000 people had phoned in to seek help in the
first three months this year, the official said, describing the
services as "highly efficient and helpful".
</P>
<P>
It was an important measure for the Chinese justice departments
to enhance reform of the justice administration while providing
better legal services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Membership to Make China's SOEs More Competitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Membership in the World Trade
Organization (WTO) will make China's state-owned enterprises (SOEs)
more competitive, according to a commentary in China Economic
Times.
</P>
<P>
Joining the WTO will promote China's SOEs to the market
frontier, and accelerate their reforms, the article said.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued during Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's
visit to the United States, the U.S. committed itself to firmly
supporting China's entry into the WTO this year.
</P>
<P>
Some SOEs may continue to operate at a loss after China enters
the WTO, and there could be more of them closing and laying-off
more workers. But in the long run, all of these enterprises will
have to become more competitive under the pressure of competition,
it said.
</P>
<P>
There is now a condition of competitive imbalance between SOEs
and non-SOEs in China, as SOEs are under the protection of
government administration, while the non-SOEs are not.
</P>
<P>
However, statistics show that of the more than 7,680 large and
medium-sized SOEs, those operating in the red exceed 2,300,
accounting for about 30 percent of all state enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
