<HEADLINE> Dew Project Improves Shaanxi Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Dew Project has provided more
than 4.2 million people living in arid areas in northwestern
Shaanxi Province with adequate water for both consumption and
irrigation.
</P>
<P>
The local government launched the project in 1996, with more
than one billion yuan (120 million US dollars) in provincial
allocations over the past three years for the construction of 10,
000 water-supply projects, including wells, ponds and water
storage pits for family-use.
</P>
<P>
The water projects have played a major role in helping Shaanxi
overcome problems related to this year's lingering dry spells.
</P>
<P>
The local meteorological department reported that there was
practically no snowfall or precipitation in 72 Shaanxi counties
during the November-March period. In addition, temperatures in the
region have averaged one to three degrees centigrade higher than
normal.
</P>
<P>
Water flow rates for three major rivers in the province are 33
percent below rates in previous years. The severe drought has
impacted 1.2 million ha of cropland, or 70 percent of the total
acreage planted to cross-winter crops.
</P>
<P>
Water projects built over the past three years are currently
operating at full capacity. The province has allocated 120 million
yuan (145,000 US dollars) to construct irrigation facilities.
Moreover, 340 drought-combatting brigades staffed by over two
million local officials and workers have been formed.
</P>
<P>
Irrigation efforts have been carried out on over 900,000
hectares of Shaanxi's arid land.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sales Drop for China's Large Department Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey on China's 286
leading department stores reveals that the growth rate of their
total sales volume, retail sales volume and profits all slowed
down last year, reaching the lowest point in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by the Information Center under the
State Administration of Internal Trade (SAIT).
</P>
<P>
The total sales volume of the 286 large department stores hit
some 107 billion yuan, slightly up 0.29 percent on an annual basis;
and retail sales volume was 85.2 billion yuan, up 2.62 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's 1998 total retail sales volume was 2,915.3
billion yuan, up 6.8 percent, according to the SAIT survey.
</P>
<P>
Profits of these department stores exceeded 2.23 billion yuan,
a year-on-year drop of 16.93 percent. About one half of them were
making less profit and 53 of them are even losing money.
</P>
<P>
There are 221 department stores whose sales volume was over 100
million yuan each last year, including 22 each with more than one
billion yuan in sales.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts noted that the overall pattern of the
commercial market remained quite unchanged and that retail sales
were highest in downtown areas of large cities, Beijing and
Shanghai in particular.
</P>
<P>
Seven department stores in Beijing and eight in Shanghai were
labeled as the top ten best-performing ones in terms of the above-
mentioned three indicators.
</P>
<P>
Veteran department stores nationwide still have a huge
attraction. Beijing Wangfujing Department Store and Wuhan
Department Store were knocked out of the top ten, replaced by a
Nanjing department store and a Wuxi department store.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
