<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Tea Production to Drop in 1999: Authority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's tea production in 1999 is
expected to drop by about 35 percent due to droughts in many parts
of the tea- growing country, the Kenya Tea Development Authority
(KTDA) has said.
</P>
<P>
The dry spell between December and February is likely to result
in a drop from the record-breaking 750 million kilograms of leaf
last year to about 500 million kg this year, managing director of
the authority Eustace Karanja said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, improved management of tea factory companies and
purchase of new trucks had resulted in decreasing operation costs,
the Daily Nation newspaper Thursday quoted Karanja as saying.
</P>
<P>
The managing director noted that prices at tea auctions were
also not so good as those of last year.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the restructuring and liberalization of the tea
industry, the director said that the move would give farmers more
pay and also lower cost of production leaving bigger profit
margins for farmers.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kenya Tea Development Authority, which would
transform itself into Kenya Tea Development Agency, would be
acting as a private management body helping to manage the tea
factory companies.
</P>
<P>
The procurement of fertilizers, computers, trucks and other
machinery would be also continue to be done through the authority
for greater efficiency, he added.
</P>
<P>
The on-going restructuring and liberalization of small holder
tea sub- sector and the Kenya Tea Development Authority will be
finalized by January 2000, the director said.
</P>
<P>
Tea is one of Kenya's major foreign exchange earners. Last
year, Kenya earned about 580 million U.S. dollars through
exporting tea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
