<HEADLINE> Largest Auction House to Sell Famous Chinese Paintings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- China's largest auction house
will offer for sale some rare paintings featuring traditional
characteristics at auctions scheduled from April 20 to 22 in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The auctioneers estimate that the well-known work, Lijiang
River - Sailing Home, created by Li Keran, who died in 1989, could
fetch up to 2.6 million yuan (313,000 U.S. dollars) in anticipated
hot bidding.
</P>
<P>
These Spring auctions by the China Guardian Auctions Company
will include more than 500 ancient, modern and contemporary
Chinese paintings, Hu Yanyan, chief of the company's Chinese
Paintings and Calligraphy Section, told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Domestic and overseas collectors are expected to vigorously bid
for 22 paintings by Master Zhang Daqian, a big name among Chinese
painters who died in 1983.
</P>
<P>
One work by Xu Beihong (1895-1953) depicting six steeds is
expected to bring up to 800,000 yuan, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
"It's very difficult appraise Chinese paintings," Hu said, "
therefore, collectors showed less interest in the them in the past.
"
</P>
<P>
"But the market is thriving now," she said.
</P>
<P>
Over 85 percent of the traditional Chinese painting works
offered in October during Guardian's Autumn auctions were sold, Hu
added.
</P>
<P>
She said such painting are well received nowadays, and works of
famous imperial painters of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), such as
Wang Hui and Zhang Zongcang are favorites among collectors.
</P>
<P>
Ancient Chinese paintings were very much in the limelight
during Christie's auctions last month in New York.
</P>
<P>
Christie's of Hong Kong will also hold similar auctions later
this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
