<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Poets: What Does Literature Brings To You? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- There is a group of young and
energetic people in the remote areas of northwest China's Gansu
Province and southwest China's Yunnan Province who wrote poetry in
their leisure time when they are not doing farm work.
</P>
<P>
In May, the monthly publication Poetry Magazine will publish an
edition of the works of some of these young poets from the poor
mountainous areas of Gansu Province, and a magazine called "
Everyone" in Yunnan Province will publish a survey in its next
edition with answers from 15 poets from the rural areas of Yunnan
Province to the question, "What does literature bring to you?"
</P>
<P>
This shows that the poems of these young farmers are beginning
to draw attention, said Ye Yanbing, deputy chief editor of Poetry
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
Ye said his magazine sent editors to Lintan County in
mountainous area in southern part of Gansu Province, which is 3,
000 meters above sea level and has a low per-hectare grain output,
to do some poverty-relief work last year.
</P>
<P>
The editors were surprised to find that in this poverty-
stricken area many people were writing poetry, and some of their
poems were very good, according to the Shanghai Wenhui Daily. "We
receive works from these poor farmer poets almost every day," said
Lei Pingyang, an editor at 'Everyone', "and they come not only
from one particular area, but from all over the country."
</P>
<P>
There is usually a story behind the poems in which the author
tells of his or her bitter living conditions which makes you sad,
Lei said. "Some poems I have received are written on small writing
pads used by middle-school students."
</P>
<P>
"But these young poets really show their true feelings in their
poems and are very conscientious about their writing," said Lei. "
This makes their work different from the literature of urban
residents."
</P>
<P>
"Their poems, sprouting from the real life of country people,
are full of love for their hometowns, and full of passion and the
confidence of youth," noted Poetry Magazine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
