<HEADLINE> Jordan Uses Most Foreign Grants on Watdsrojects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has spent over half the 770
million dollars of foreign financial grants in 1998 to rehabilitate
the aging water supply systems of the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
SoK954 percent or 382 million dollars was used on wr projects
across the country in 1998, an increase of 37 percent over 1994, a
news letterthe Ministry of Planning said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increased spending on the water supply system, a
serious water crisis was expected this summer due to a dragged-out
drought since the second half of 1998, experts warned.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom needs 1,544 million cubic meters of water to meet the
demand this summer while the amount available was only 1,417 million
cubic meters, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials feared that a water dispute with Israel might
further worsen the water supply situation in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which should provide Jordan with 55 million cubic meters
of water each summer under the 1994 peace treaty, has proposed to reduce
its water supplies by 40 percent this summer, cit)!o{evere drought in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli suggestion was firmly rejected by Jordanian officials,
who take the water clauses as the key elements in the 1994 peace
treaty as well as bilateral ties.
</P>
