<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Drought in New Zealand Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- La Nina weather patterns are
likely to continue in New Zealand and can bring drought to Otaga,
an important sheep and beef farming area on South Island, for the
third year in a row, the Dominion reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted Director Rick Pridmore of
the National Institute for Water and Atmospheric Research as
saying scientists are "pretty sure" La Nina will persist through
winter, bringing further dry weather to Otaga.
</P>
<P>
Continued La Nina weather patterns will also be likely to bring
 drought to Hawke's Bay on North Island and Marlborough on South
Island, and can "spell disaster for farmers already struggling to
survive after two years of drought", he said.
</P>
<P>
Senior climate scientist Reid Basher said the severity of the
drought experienced by Otaga this summer will normally only be
expected once every 30 years.
</P>
<P>
According to officials of the New Zealand Ministry of
Agriculture and Forestry, farm gate losses from last year's
drought are estimated at 460 million NZ dollars (248 million U.S.
dollars), this year's drought costs another 200 million NZ dollars
(108 million U.S. dollars), and the flow-on effects next year are
expected to cost farmers another 300 million NZ dollars (162
million U.S. dollars), a total farm gate loss of 960 million NZ
dollars (518 million U.S. dollars). The total cost to the New
Zealand economy is estimated at around 3.5 billion NZ dollars
(1.89 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
