<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Economic Growth to Drop to 24th in World in 2000: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia was expected to slip
from the world's fourth fastest growing economy in 1998 to 24th
place next year, according to a quarterly world financial markets
report.
</P>
<P>
JP Morgan's World Financial Markets report released Thursday
said Australia's economic growth rate was expected to slow
substantially this year from the 4.9 percent calendar year result
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said in early March that
the Australian economy grew at 4.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Economic growth will surely slow in Australia in 1999," JP
Morgan senior economist John Kyriakopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly report said gross domestic product (GDP) growth
was expected to drop to 2.7 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Australian federal Treasurer Peter Costello said Wednesday the
Australian economy would slow this year, adding "if the slowing
comes back to two to three percent, that'll be a fantastic
outcome".
</P>
<P>
"Australia has mostly weathered the storm from Asia's
recession, but not without some economic damage," Kyriakopoulos
told the Australian Associated Press Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"For example, while big spending consumers have been the engine
of recent GDP (gross domestic product) growth, they have not
prevented a sharp slowing in overall private spending growth,
which is now at 1993 and 1996 levels, when the RBA (the Reserve
Bank of Australia) was cutting interest rates."
</P>
<P>
Kyriakopoulos also said the boost in infrastructure from the
2000 Olympics was fading as construction came close to completion
and residential investment was experiencing a modest downturn.
</P>
<P>
"However, exports could improve as trading partner growth
rebounds, but mining investment will remain depressed for some
time," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Households are still benefiting from historically low and
stable interest rates, rising real wages and continuing job gains
which have boosted consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
"But public sector employees will not receive substantial pay
rises again for several years as the federal government aims to
keep a tight rein on spending."
</P>
<P>
For world financial markets, the JP Morgan report forecast
faster global growth by the second half of this year, with Japan's
recession almost over.
</P>
<P>
"The better tone to global growth can occur even though a
slowing of the U.S. economy later in the year is a key feature of
the forecast," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
