<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar and GDP Growth to Rise: ABARE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Growth in Australian real gross
domestic product (GDP) would jump from three percent in the fiscal
year of 1999-2000 to 3.5 percent for the next four years, with the
Australian dollar rising to 72 U.S. cents in the same period, the
government's chief commodities forecaster predicted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A new report by the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and
Resource Economics (ABARE) predicts GDP growth will remain at 3.5
percent until the fiscal year of 2003-2004 before declining to 3.3
percent for 2004-06 and then 3.2 percent for the fiscal year of
2006-2008.
</P>
<P>
ABARE then assumes a growth rate of three percent for the next
seven years until the fiscal year of 2014-2015.
</P>
<P>
However, JP Morgan's World Financial Markets report released
Thursday said Australia's economic growth rate was expected to
drop to 2.7 percent this year from the 4.9 percent calendar year
result in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Australian federal Treasurer Peter Costello said Wednesday the
Australian economy would slow this year, adding "if the slowing
comes back to two to three percent, that'll be a fantastic
outcome".
</P>
<P>
ABARE expects the Australian dollar, which was buying 63.94
U.S. cents at the close of trade Wednesday, to gradually
strengthen from 65 U.S. cents in the fiscal year of 1999-2000,
which starts on July 1, 1999, to 68 U.S. cents in the following
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
It said the Australian dollar would cut the 70 U.S. cent
barrier the next year and then strengthening slowly again to reach
a peak of 75 U.S. cents from 2006-2009.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar is then expected to decline slightly to
be worth about 72 U.S. cents by the year 2014-15.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices (in 1999 dollars) are forecast to rise from
12.84 U.S. dollars per barrel in the fiscal year of 1999-2000 to
15.40 U.S. dollars in the fiscal year of 2001-2002 before
gradually declining to 11.50 U.S. dollars in the fiscal year of
2014-2015.
</P>
<P>
ABARE has also predicted Australia's population is likely to
rise from 19.1 million people in the fiscal year of 1999-2000 to
21.6 million people by the fiscal year of 2014-2015. 
</P>
</TEXT>
