<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Successfully Test-fires Shaheen-I Missile  by Wang Wei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan successfully
test-fired a Shaheen-I ballistic missile Thursday morning, about
24 hours after its launching of a Ghauri-II missile, a Foreign
Office statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Shaheen ballistic missile, a surface-to-surface missile,
was test-fired at 09:50 a.m. local time (0450 GMT) from Sonmiani,
around 75 kilometers northwest of Pakistan's southern port city of
Karachi, an informed source told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Shaheen missile hit the target in the desert area of Nok
Kundi in Pakistan's southwestern province of Balochistan bordering
Iran after a little more than five minutes, the source said.
</P>
<P>
One source from the Kahuta Research Laboratory, when contacted,
said that the government is expected to announce the concerned
details later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Office has called for a press briefing at 14:45
p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statement by the Foreign Office said earlier that "the test
concludes, for now, the series of SSM (surface-to- surface
missile) flight tests involving solid and liquid fuel rocket motor
technologies, which started yesterday (Wednesday)."
</P>
<P>
However, the source from the Kahuta Research Laboratory
indicated that Pakistan is likely to conduct more tests of
Ghauri-II ballistic missile with an expanded range.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan successfully test fired a Ghauri-II missile Wednesday
morning after its successful launching of Ghauri-I a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said in a briefing in Ormara navy
base in Balochistan that the Ghauri-II missile, with a payload
capacity of 1,000 kilograms, had an effective target range of
2,000 kilometers, one-third longer than the earlier version of
Ghauri-I, which has a range of 1,500 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Due to the non-availability of enough depth in Pakistan
required to carry out the test to its full range, the Ghauri-II
was tested at a reduced range of 1,150 kilometers, said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that Pakistan will carry out another test
of Ghauri-II with an effective target range, and target is to be
set on the Arabian sea.
</P>
<P>
Shaheen, with a range of 600 kilometers, employs a solid fuel
motor and can be tipped with any type of warhead, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
However, sources from the test site said the flight range of
Shaheen-I was 700 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Shaheen-I missile, 13-meter long, weighs around 9 tons and
has a maximum range of 750 kilometers with a payload of 1,000
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that a second more advanced Shaheen-II with
a range of 2,300 kilometers is ready and waiting to be tested.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no announcement of when or whether that the
Shaheen-II would be tested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
