<HEADLINE> E. African States Fighting Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
are taking measures to fight money laundering which has emerged
following trade liberalization and harmonization of monetary
policies in the east African region.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Tanzania has drafted regulations under the Banking
Act regarding account opening procedures.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has also spread knowledge on money laundering
among staff of commercial banks, Tanzania's Daily News reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya has trained its staff and policemen
to identify laundered funds. It has also drafted guidelines to be
issued to commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, the government has assigned the Law Reform
Commission the task to draft a law on money laundering.
</P>
<P>
Executives of the central banks of the three countries, who
held a meeting in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha earlier this
week, have suggested drafting laws which will be as stern as
forfeiting laundered funds.
</P>
<P>
The central banks have also pledged to sensitize politicians
and the public to the danger of money laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
