<HEADLINE> Turkey to Send Troops to Albania on Humanitarian Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has decided to send over 100
soldiers to Albania for Humanitarian operations, Turkish Hurriyet
(Freedom) daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said this is the first time that Turkish land troops
will take part in operations of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) since it launched air strikes against Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said on Wednesday that
Turkey maintains a military force in Albania "for humanitarian
purposes only."
</P>
<P>
The paper added that the Turkish land troops will be deployed at
the Elbasan refugee camp in Albania, which is close to the Yugoslav
province of Kosovo and was built by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been supporting the NATO's military air strikes on
Yugoslavia, which resulted in tens of thousands of Kosovo refugees
fleeing to neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem has said that Turkey is likely to
accept more refugees if their number increases.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had earlier promised to accept 20,000 Kosovo refugees and
so far 9,300 Kosovars have entered Turkey. 
</P>
