<HEADLINE> ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (31) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 31 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
What are the two roles that the Chief Executive of the Macao
Special Administrative Region has?
</P>
<P>
Article 45 of the Basic Law says the Chief Executive of the
Macao Special Administrative Region shall be head of the Macao
Special Administrative Region who represents the region.
</P>
<P>
It is clear from this article that his first role is as the
highest official of the region.
</P>
<P>
The MSAR is an administrative region under the jurisdiction of
the Central People's Government and its Chief Executive is elected
by the Election Committee composed of local people.
</P>
<P>
As such, the Chief Executive shall, according to the
stipulations of the Basic Law, be accountable to the Central
People's Government and to the MSAR in accordance with the Basic
law.
</P>
<P>
To allocate the Chief Executive with the role of the highest
local officer conforms to the status of a highly autonomous region
in a unified country.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the relationship between the Central Government
and the MSAR, for instance, the Chief Executive shall implement,
on behalf of the MSAR, the directives issued by the Central
Government on matters under its responsibility.
</P>
<P>
As for the internal affairs of the region, the Chief Executive
may sign the bills adopted by the Legislative Council and
promulgate laws in his capacity as the highest local officer.
</P>
<P>
According to Article 62 of the Basic Law, the second role of
the Chief Executive is head of the government of MSAR who takes
charge of the day-to-day work of its government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
