<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (32) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 32 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
What is the nature of the Executive Council of the Macao
Special Administrative Region?
</P>
<P>
Article 56 of the Basic Law says the MSAR shall establish an
executive council. The Executive Council shall not be an
administrative organ, but an organ to assist the Chief Executive
in making policies.
</P>
<P>
The members of the Executive Council shall be Chinese citizens
who are permanent residents of the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Council shall be composed of seven to 11 persons
to be appointed by the Chief Executive from among the principal
officials of the executive authorities, members of the Legislative
Council and public figures. The term of office of members of the
Executive Council shall not extend beyond the expiry of the term
of office of the Chief Executive who appoints them.
</P>
<P>
But members of the original Executive Council shall remain in
office until the new Chief Executive is selected.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Council shall meet at least one a month and such
meetings shall be presided over by the Chief Executive who may, as
he or she deems necessary, invite other persons concerned to sit
in on such meetings.
</P>
<P>
It is the main function of the Executive Council to be
consulted by the Chief Executive before the latter makes important
policy decisions, introduces bills to the Legislative Council,
formulates administrative regulations or dissolves the Legislative
Council, except for the appointment, removal and disciplining of
officials and the adoption of measures in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
If the Chief Executive does not accept a majority opinion of
the Executive Council, he or she shall put the specific reasons on
record.
</P>
<P>
At present, there is a similar body in Macao known as the
Consultative Council which is composed of 10 members and presided
over by the Governor of Macao or his representative.
</P>
<P>
The Consultative Council's main function is to furnish the
Governor with opinions on the bills to be submitted by the
Governor to the Legislative Council, the laws promulgated by the
Legislative Council and the guiding principles on economic and
administrative matters of the Macao region so that the Governor
will come to a better decision or policy.
</P>
<P>
Such opinions have no binding force on the Governor. To some
extent, the Executive Council as provided for by the Basic law is
similar to the system of the existing Consultative Council in
Macao.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chief Executive of the MSAR shall have a legal
status totally different from that of the present Governor. And
the Executive Council needs not to be linked or converged with the
original Consultative Council. more

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
