<HEADLINE> Pak Successfully Test-fires Shaheen-I Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan successfully
test-fired a Shaheen-I ballistic missile Thursday morning, about
24 hours after its launching of a Ghauri-II missile, a Foreign
Office statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Shaheen ballistic missile was test-fired at 09:50 a.m.
local time (0450 GMT) from a site near Pakistan's southern port
city of Karachi, an official from the Pakistan Atomic Energy
Commission told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Shaheen, with a range of 600 kilometers, employs a solid fuel
motor and can be tipped with any type of warhead, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
However, sources from the test site said the flight range of
Shaheen-I was 700 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
One source from the Kahuta Research Laboratory, when contacted,
said more data is still awaited.
</P>
<P>
The missile, 13-meter long, weighs around 9 tons and has a
maximum range of 750 kilometers with a payload of 1,000 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
As a response to India's Agni-II missile flight test last
Sunday, the Shaheen missile test-firing is following Pakistan's
Wednesday launching of a Ghauri-II ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
"These flight tests have strengthened the national security and
will help in maintaining strategic balance in South Asia," said
the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
