<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Approves 76 Investment  Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Investment Centre
(ZIC) has approved 76 projects with a total investment of 193
million U.S. dollars in the first quarter of the year with a
potential of creating 4,300 jobs, the daily Herald reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The major project, valued at 128 million U.S. dollars, will see
the expansion of the telecommunications network, which is an
essential infrastructure in investment promotion.
</P>
<P>
The second-largest project involves mineral exploration and the
 development, while some of the projects are in agriculture,
tourism, construction, transport and commercial sectors.
</P>
<P>
In an interview on Wednesday, Executive Director of ZIC
Nicholas Ncube said investment approvals had declined slightly
compared to the same period last year, but improved in value
terms.
</P>
<P>
He said investors with a long-term view have continued to show
interest in the available investment opportunities and are
enjoying the benefits of improved infrastructure, an educated
workforce and a diverse industrial base.
</P>
<P>
The current economic problems were not unique to Zimbabwe alone
and resembled a transitional process common with previously
controlled economies, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "We need to mount our own publicity campaign to
dispel the bad image that has been created in the international
press." 
</P>
</TEXT>
