<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu: Chinese, U.S. Leaders dedicated to Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOSTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji said here Wednesday that both Chinese and U.S. leaders have
been dedicated to Sino-U.S. friendship despite ups and downs in
the relations between the two countries during the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of three Chinese generations, including Mao Zedong,
Deng Xiaoping and Jiang Zemin, have made unremitting efforts to
maintain and develop Sino-U.S. relations, Zhu said while
delivering a speech at a gathering in the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology (MIT).
</P>
<P>
He said American leaders, both Republican and Democratic, have
followed a common policy of friendly cooperation with China in the
past two decades.
</P>
<P>
President Richard Nixon, a Republican, re-opened the U.S.-China
ties, which was followed by the establishment of diplomatic
relations with China by President Jimmy Carter, a Democratic.
Later on, Presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush, of the
Republican Party, further pushed forward bilateral ties, Zhu told
the gathering, which was attended by 1,200 people.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, he said, President Jiang Zemin and President Bill
Clinton, of the Democratic Party, have made a successful exchange
of visits and have decided to work toward establishing a
constructive strategic partnership, marking a new phase of
development in Sino-U.S. relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
To develop Sino-U.S. relations is the bipartisan policy of the
United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said a constructive strategic partnership between China and
the United States will benefit the peoples of the two countries,
the people of the world, world peace and international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the so-called "China's threat," Zhu said China
does not constitute any threat to the United States, nor will it
do so in future.
</P>
<P>
"China is not your potential adversary, nor your enemy, but
your friend in whom you can trust," Zhu told the audience.
</P>
<P>
Zhu arrived in the United States on April 6 to pay an eight-day
official visit to the country, the first by a Chinese premier in
15 years.
</P>
<P>
Zhu quoted President Bill Clinton as saying that the United
States has 6,000 pieces of nuclear weapons, while China has only
20 to 30 pieces. "I wonder how President Clinton got the figures,
which even I haven't heard of. But I agree with him that the
United States is far more superior than China in nuclear arms
stocks and that China poses no threat to the United States
militarily," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who arrived in Boston, the last stop of his current trip,
from New York Wednesday morning, said that it is important for
China and the United States to build a constructive strategic
partnership, which conforms to the interests of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the United States, Zhu met with many
American public figures including Congress people, federal and
local government officials as well as heads of news organizations
and executives of financial institutions and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier said he got an impression from his contacts
with people here from various walks of life that ordinary
Americans are supportive for the development of Sino-U.S.relations,
which laid the foundation for further advancement of friendly
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu recalled that when he said this to President Clinton on
telephone on Tuesday, the president replied, "I shared the view
with you."
</P>
<P>
Zhu said he is convinced that the American people stand for a
cooperative relations with China and support its efforts to join
the World Trade Organization (WTO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
