<HEADLINE> Taiwan Smuggler Executed on the Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The captain of a Taiwan fishing
boat was executed today for attempting to smuggle more than 73
million counterfeit yuan (8.8 million US dollars) into Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
Lin Jingchuan was caught by customs officials in a coastguard
cutter in February 1997 as his boat, with three other crew members,
sailed in Shantou in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
His conviction was confirmed today by the Supreme People's
Court after an initial appeal and the sentence carried out soon
after. His fellow smugglers were all given life imprisonment and
had 50,000 yuan of their possessions confiscated by the
Intermediate People's Court of Shantou. Lin also had 100,000 yuan
worth of possessions confiscated.
</P>
<P>
Three other separate smuggling cases saw four more Taiwanese
and four Hong Kong people given prison sentences ranging from four
years to life, in addition to fines.
</P>
<P>
In another customs breakthrough, Li Wei, also Taiwanese, was
caught at a Guangzhou airport in February last year attempting to
smuggle 60,000 fake US dollars into Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He will serve 14 years in prison and pay a fine of 100,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
And four Hong Kong residents were caught in January last year
at Jinan Airport in east China's Shandong Province when they
failed to declare 128 kilograms of gold hidden in their luggage.
</P>
<P>
The Intermediate People's Court of Jinan meted out a seven year
imprisonment sentence on one, a five year sentence on two and a
four year sentence on the final accused.
</P>
<P>
According to the Supreme People's Court, the nine defendants
appealed to the Higher People's Court in Guangdong and Shandong
respectively after their first trial but all were rejected leaving
the original verdicts standing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
