<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soft Drink Industry Grows Fast in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The soft drink industry has been
growing fast in Bangladesh, the latest issue of the Dhaka-based
weekly Economic Times reported.
</P>
<P>
There was only one multi-national beverage factory in the
country in the early 1970s, and now four large companies are
marketing their products across the country and some small
companies are also active in the market.
</P>
<P>
Beverage factories produced soft drinks worth 401 million taka
(about 8.35 million U.S. dollars) in the 1989-90 fiscal year, on
the basis of fixed price, with an estimated net value addition of
165 million taka (about 3.44 million dollars), according to
figures from the Bangladesh Bureau Statistics.
</P>
<P>
In the year 1995-96, the production in the beverage industry
rose to 1,593 million taka (about 33.19 million dollars),
registering a value addition of 963 million taka (about 20.06
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The beverage industry recorded a staggering 397 percent
expansion in a span of six years, while the profit from both
production and sales rose to 60.45 percent in 1995-96 from 41.14
percent in 1989-90.
</P>
<P>
The consumption of soft drink also registered a marked increase
over the years, according to the report. The sales of soft drink
jumped from 70 million bottles in 1984-85 to 259 million bottles
in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that in 12 years, while the population
increased by 24 percent, the selling of soft drink increased by
270 percent, and the per head soft drink of 1.4 bottles in 1984-85
grew to 2.7 bottles per head in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
However, the lion's share of the country's soft drink market is
controlled by foreign brands, with almost 50 percent of the market
dominated by Coca Cola brands, followed by Pepsi Cola, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
