<HEADLINE> Milosevic Willing to Talk With Kosovo Ethnic Albanian Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Gregor Gysi, first German mediator
to Belgrade, briefed the press on his talks with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic Wednesday, saying Milosevic would
like to negotiate directly with Kosovo ethnic Albanian leaders
under the mediation of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Gysi, parliamentary chairman of the Democratic Socialist Party
(DSP) group who returned here after his one-day trip to Yugoslavia,
said Milosevic promised that all Kosovar refugees fleeing NATO
airstrikes could return home in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia sticks to its stance of refusing forces of NATO and
the United Nations to enter Kosovo, except for UN civilian
observers, he added.
</P>
<P>
During his stay there, Gysi visited the Zastava Plane
Manufacture Plant, which was destroyed by NATO missiles.
</P>
<P>
Shocked by damages imposed by NATO's air strikes, he criticized
the German media for keeping quiet on the issue while making a hue
about the sufferings of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that his party will continue opposing NATO's
military actions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The DSP, the only parliament party with unanimous opposition to
NATO air strikes, has organized several large scale demonstrations
for the purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
