<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Reform Military with U.S., British Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Romania is set to accelerate
military reforms with the assistance of the United States and
Britain in a bid to improve the fighting capability and achieve,
as soon as possible, integration with NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
Romanian leaders talked Wednesday with a visiting U.S. military
delegation on a plan regarding Romania's military reforms.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which has been jointly introduced by the country's
Defense Ministry and experts from the United States and Britain,
was submitted to the parliament for ratification, the state news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Major General Henry Kievenaar, head of the
delegation, Prime Minister Radu Vasile tentatively explained the
direction of Romania's military reforms in scale and equipment.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that the plan meets entirely with the needs of the
defined purposes.
</P>
<P>
Petre Roman, President of the Romanian Senate, said after
meeting General Kievenaar that the parliament would consider
passing a long-term budget for five to 10 years for the defense
ministry to guarantee the stability of the reforms.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he urged that prior to beginning the reforms, the
fighting capability of the military should attempt to reach at
least 80 percent of NATO's criteria under existing conditions.
</P>
<P>
Romania has been seeking NATO membership for many years.
</P>
</TEXT>
