<HEADLINE> Xinhua Economic News Summary at 0430 GMT April 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Crude oil prices fell Wednesday as data on U.S. and
European petroleum inventories proved less supportive to the
market than expected.
</P>
<P>
Benchmark Brent blend crude oil last closed 28 cents lower at
14.92 dollars a barrel in London.
</P>
<P>
Weekly figures from the American Petroleum Institute (API)
showed a rise in U.S. inventories of gasoline, diesel and heating
oil and higher crude stocks.(London-Oil Price)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The industrial exports of Egypt's free zones rose by
32 percent in the first quarter this year over the same period
last year, an official in charge of free zone issues said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's free zones exported 120 million U.S. dollars worth of
industrial goods from January to March in 1999, 2 9 million
dollars more than those in the same period in 1998, Chairman of
the General Authority and Free Zones Ibrahim Fawzi told reporters.
(Egypt-Free Zones)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- The development and adoption of Internet
appliances will explode in the United States during the next 12
months, according to a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
By leveraging the capabilities of the Internet, the report
said, Internet appliances stand ready to revolutionize the way
that information is used and accessed by enabling universal access
-- the ability to access any information, over any network and
from any device.(US-Internet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said
Wednesday that the aim of the Department of Finance to bring down
interest rates to 10 percent within the first half of the year is
realistic.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Post Thursday quoted Singson as saying that the
monetary authorities are supporting the move authored by Finance
Secretary Edgardo Espiritu since this encourages greater economic
activities.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the year and imposed a 3 percent cut in the
liquidity reserves requirement for banks, thereby providing more-
than-sufficient funds to "pump-prime" the economy.(Philipines-
Central Bank)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippines' foreign debt rose by 2.3843 billion
U.S. dollars to 47.817 billion U.S. dollars in end-1998 from 45.
433 billion U.S. dollars the previous year, the Manila Times
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a recently released report of the
Philippine Central Bank as saying that the increase was due to
more foreign borrowing of the public sector including the national
government and foreign exchange revaluation.(Philipines-Foreign
Debt) 
</P>
