<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Fighters, Two Helicopters Crash in Bosnia: NATO Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The TV station quoted an unidentified senior official with the
NATO-led Multinational Stabilization Force in Bosnia as saying
that only at 10 a.m. Wednesday morning, a NATO fighter plane,
which was hit by Yugoslav anti-air fire, crashed in the Gorazde
region.
</P>
<P>
At nearly the same time, another NATO fighter plane, reportedly
hit by Yugoslav anti-air forces, crashed in Majevica while
struggling to fly back to the airport in Tuzla, the TV station
said.
</P>
<P>
A third NATO fighter plane, reportedly hit by Yugoslav anti-
aircraft fire, also crashed in a mountain area while trying to fly
back to the Tuzla airport, the TV station reported.
</P>
<P>
Previously, another NATO fighter plane reportedly crashed in
the Pale region while trying to fly back to the airport in
Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
Two NATO helicopters are said to have crashed in Bosnia's Serb
Republic. Only two out of the 37 U.S. airborne servicemen aboard
the helicopters survived.
</P>
<P>
So far, bodies of three NATO pilots have been found in Bosnia,
the NATO official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
