<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Resumes Funding for Seven Suspended Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Low quality construction was attributed to numerous cracks
which appearing in the Kunming-Luquan Highway only 18 days after
the major artery opened to traffic in May last year. The initial
project completed at a total cost of 377 million yuan, with an
estimated 100 million yuan spent on the reconstruction effort.
</P>
<P>
SDPC inspectors dispatched to examine the reconstruction of
nine projects, including the highway, in March this year discover
quality problems which prompted the suspension of government.
</P>
<P>
A recent commission circular acknowledged that the
aforementioned seven reconstruction projects basically fulfilled
standards. More than 60 million yuan allocated to reconstruction
of the highway project was used to repair cracks and reinforce
collapsed sections.
</P>
<P>
The highway reconstruction project is scheduled for completion
by the end of April. The commission noted that officials and
parties held responsible for shoddy construction have received due
punishment.
</P>
<P>
The SDPC also noted that localities responsible for the other
six projects have introduced major improvements.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the commission urged the related departments and
localities to strengthen supervision over project quality and
management in order to ensure the efficient use of government
funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
