<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Earmarks 18.2 Mln Dollars to Aid Graduate Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has earmarked
673 million baht (18.2 million U.S. dollars) from the government's
job-creation project to hire 20,000 graduates, the Bangkok Post
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The hired graduates will help educate the public about the
constitution and election methods, said election commission member
Gothom Arya.
</P>
<P>
The 20,000 university and vocational college graduates would be
employed as campaign volunteers from mid-June to mid-November, he
said.
</P>
<P>
They would be sent in teams of 50 each to 400 constituencies
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
A team coordinator would receive 8,000 baht (216 dollars)
monthly, while the other volunteers would receive 5,000 baht (137
dollars) per month.
</P>
<P>
More than one million Thais have lost their jobs as a result of
the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
To ease growing unemployment, the Thai government has been
assisting some 268,259 Thais in the past two years to find jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
