<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen Plants More Mangroves in Coastal Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The port city of Xiamen in east
China's Fujian Province plans to expand the coverage of mangrove
belts along its coastline in an effort to improve the coastal
environment.
</P>
<P>
Mangroves, which are highly suited to shallow shoal areas,
provide a favorable breeding ground for many cash aquatic products
and form a natural bulwark to filter pollutants which are know to
cause so-called "Red Tides".
</P>
<P>
However, the coverage of natural mangrove trees in the city's
coastal areas have declined in recent years due to the exploration
of resources for economic purposes. Some 30 hectares of remaining
mangrove stands are sparsely scattered along Xiamen's coastline.
</P>
<P>
The mangrove plantation project, initiated by the Xiamen
Forestry Department and Xiamen University, is expected to increase
the coverage by about 107 hectares. Large-scale planting drives
will be initiated through May this year.
</P>
<P>
The project will represent the city's first large-scale effort
to plant mangroves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
