<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tomato Nutrient May Protect Men From Prostate Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- American researchers have
found the first direct evidence that the tomato nutrient lycopene
may protect men against prostate cancer by shrinking tumors and
preventing them from spreading.
</P>
<P>
A study, released at a meeting of the American Association for
Cancer Research in Philadelphia, said that researchers from the
Karmanos Cancer Institute in Detroit gave lycopene, the nutrient
that makes tomatoes red, to men who were about to undergo surgery
to remove cancerous glands.
</P>
<P>
According to Tuesday's edition of Washington Post, the study
involved 33 men who were randomly assigned to take lycopene or
nothing for 30 days before their prostate operations.
</P>
<P>
Before surgery the volunteers showed no obvious signs that
their cancer had spread. After surgery, the doctors found cancer
tissue was less likely to extend to the edges of the lycopene
users' prostate glands. And pre-cancerous cells in their prostates
were less abnormal looking.
</P>
<P>
"This suggests that lycopene results in a decrease of the tumor
size and makes the cancer less aggressive," said Omar Kucuk who
directed the study.
</P>
<P>
Lycopene has become a trendy nutritional supplement, and large
population surveys have suggested that those who eat plenty of
tomatoes, the primary natural source of lycopene, are less likely
to get prostate cancer or other malignancies.
</P>
<P>
Findings by researchers from the Karmanos Cancer Institute
confirm and support the above surveys.
</P>
<P>
However the researchers warned that their study is small, and
cautioned against routine use of lycopene supplements without
further evidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boat Accidents Frequent in Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua)-- China had 46 accidents involving
the sinking of 11 boats and causing 101 deaths in southern China's
Guangdong, Guangxi and Yunnan provinces during the first ten
months of last year, according to a Guangming Daily report.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the number of boating accidents is probably
much greater in all of southern China, as the water-rich region is
filled with boats and ships.
</P>
<P>
The article quoted an official from the Guangxi Shipping
Administration as saying that scant attention to navigation
regulations and safety measures, as well as the inadequate
education are among the reasons for all these accidents.
</P>
<P>
The boats of the farmers in the region, mostly made of wood,
are often poorly maintained, said the official, adding that some
boats which should have been scrapped are still being used.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper called for more stringent supervision and
management of water transport, and greater efforts to improve
awareness of safety measures among the farmers who own boats.
</P>
<P>
The report also lauded the city of Guilin in Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region for its building of more bridges to better
contain water traffic.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Guilin raised over 1.8 million yuan to build 76
bridges, substantially reducing the number of boats operating on
its rivers, and dramatically reducing the number of accidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic: No NATO Civilian Observers in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 14 (Xinhua) - Yugoslavia will allow no foreign
troops in Kosovo under any circumstances and any future civilian
observers must come from countries not involved in NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia, announced visiting Belarus President Alexander
Lukashenko here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press conference with his Yugoslav counterpart
Slobodan Milosevic, Lukashenko said he had asked Milosevic if any
compromise was possible in Yugoslavia's fight against NATO, which
has bombed the country for three weeks over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia is ready to accept civilian observers from the
United Nations or representatives of other countries. Civilian
observers, not army or police teams," Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
"Those representatives must be from the countries which are not
involved in recent NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. We must have in
mind that this is the final point of view of Yugoslavia, not only
us, but the NATO countries too."
</P>
<P>
For his part, Milosevic said he had discussed the issue of
Yugoslavia's accession to the loose union between Belarus and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
He said he had already submitted an official application to
President Lukashenko and Russian President Boris Yeltsin, adding
that he expected that the two would make an official reply in the
interests of the three peoples.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko said he was pleased to hear from Milosevic that
Yugoslavia does not want to draw Russia and Belarus into the war.
</P>
<P>
"I see that this is not a simple process and that it takes a
lot of time. I said that we'll do everything to do things as fast
as we can. But we must be absolutely clear and do it in the right
way." 
</P>
</TEXT>
