<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Debt Hits 47.8 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' foreign debt rose
by 2.3843 billion U.S. dollars to 47.817 billion U.S. dollars in
end-1998 from 45.433 billion U.S. dollars the previous year, the
Manila Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a recently released report of the
Philippine Central Bank as saying that the increase was due to
more foreign borrowing of the public sector including the national
government and foreign exchange revaluation.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank, however, said that despite the
rise in the foreign debt, the country's debt service ratio stood
at 11.6 percent, still lower than the 36 percent recorded in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
Public sector debts which comprise 63 percent of total debts
inched up to 30.125 billion U.S. dollars from 28.623 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Obligations of the private sector slightly increased to 17.692
billion U.S. dollars from 16.81 billion U.S. dollars. Due to the
currency crisis, private firms found it hard to obtain loans from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the weakening of the U.S. dollar
against the yen last year likewise contributed to the rise in the
country's foreign exchange debts. The country's foreign loans, 25
percent of which are owed from Japanese creditors, are booked in
dollar term, thus, any movement between the greenbacks and the yen
affects its level.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said from the foreign exchange revaluation
alone, the debt rose by more than 2 billion U.S. dollars. It noted
that the yen appreciated by more than 14 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
By maturity profile, medium- and long-term debts, amounting to
40.644 billion U.S. dollars with an average maturity of 20.6 years
for the public sector debts and 7.2 years for private firms,
comprised 85 percent of the obligations.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the short-term debts comprised only 15
percent at 7.17 billion dollars, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
