<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mummy Over 1,500 Years Old Found in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A mummified baby, believed
to be between 1,500 and 2,000 years old, has been found in
Antofagasta de la Sierra of Argentina's Catamarca province.
</P>
<P>
A group of Argentine archeologists from the National University
of Tucuman (NUT) found the mummy at a height of 3,500 meters
during an excavation program, Carlos Aschero, director of the
Archeological Institute and the Museum of Natural Sciences of the
NUT, said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the mummified baby was found wrapped in cooked leather,
and covered by straw. On top of the mummy were two baskets, one
for decorating and the other containing food.
</P>
<P>
He said the baby was between two and three months old at the
time of its death and its chest had been pierced by a sea shell,
with two perforations at the height of its clavicles, which could
signify a form of ritual death.
</P>
<P>
The discovery may give more information on the burial rites,
the diet of the mother and other general information regarding the
historical period, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
