<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Network Consulting Service Market Expands Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Of all the fast-growing
markets in information technology (IT) services, the market for
network consulting and integration services is expanding rapidly
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released Wednesday by the U.S. research
firm International Data Corporation (IDC), revenues in the
worldwide market for network support and integration services grew
by almost two billion U.S. dollars in 1998 over the previous year
to reach 12.1 billion dollars. By 2003, the market will more than
double to 25.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Skilled IT employees are becoming more and more scarce while
network complexities and demands for higher-quality service are
increasing. As a result, said IDC in the report, a typical
organization's internal information service staff does not have
enough time to deal with issues like network redesign, capacity
planning and security policies.
</P>
<P>
Under these circumstances, organizations of all sizes have had
to increase their spending on network consulting and integration
services, in order to address human resource constraints, remain
ahead of the technology curve and align IT investments to core
business processes.
</P>
<P>
Integration services have come into being as technology is
increasingly becoming complex. More and more customers want
complete solutions to information problems, requiring hardware,
software and networking expertise in a multi-vendor environment.
</P>
<P>
Of all network consulting and integration services, the IDC
believes organizations will increase spending more rapidly on
security-related services.
</P>
<P>
Increased media exposure to network hackers, viruses and other
security threats has left organizations desperate to protect their
valuable data. As a result of these trends, the IDC expects end-
user spending worldwide on security consulting and integration
services to reach approximately 977 million dollars by 2003.
</P>
<P>
The United States spent 7.6 billion dollars on network
consulting and integration services in 1998, more than any other
region. Western Europe came next with 2.6 billion dollars. The
Asia-Pacific region cut spending in the same year, but the IDC
expects the region to renew enthusiasm in the long term and
increase its spending at a compound annual growth rate of 20
percent through 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Reacts Cautiously to German Plan on Kosovo Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton Administration
reacted cautiously to a German peace proposal for Kosovo on
Wednesday, saying Yugoslavia must first meet NATO's demands before
U.S. would consider any bombing pause under the plan.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the United States was
consulting with Germany about the plan unveiled early Wednesday,
which includes a temporary bombing halt to allow Yugoslavia to
begin withdrawing its troops.
</P>
<P>
He said the German plan was in line with NATO conditions for
ending the offensive against Yugoslavia. But he added, "there will
be no cessation of this air campaign until the demands are met."
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the United States had talked with Germany about
the plan proposed by German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer. "I
think it's very much in the spirit of what NATO has laid out as
the conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said the
German plan was more detailed than had been publicly revealed. "We
think it's a constructive thing to do," he said of the German
effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
