<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Rejects General Dynamics-Newport Merger Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense Department on
Wednesday rejected a merger between defense giants General
Dynamics Corp. and Newport News Shipbuilding that would have
created a single ship builder for all nuclear submarines.
</P>
<P>
The proposed two billion U.S.-dollar deal would have also
reduced competition in other sectors of military shipbuilding, and
any cost savings to the Navy would not justify that loss of
competition, Defense Secretary William Cohen said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Because the merger would collapse the two existing companies
into a single entity, there would be a reduction in the likelihood
of future competition," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
General Dynamics made an unsolicited bid for Newport News in
February. The deal required Pentagon approval and also was subject
to a review by the Justice Department's antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
If successful, General Dynamics would have dominated the
approximately 7-billion-dollar annual market for U.S. Navy ships.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas D. Chabraja, General Dynamics chairman and chief
executive officer, called the Pentagon decision "disappointing"
and said his firm has withdrawn its offer.
</P>
<P>
"General Dynamics believes that its proposed acquisition of
Newport News Shipbuilding would have meant significant savings for
the U.S. Navy, enhanced value for the shareholders of both
companies, and still preserved jobs," Chabraja said.
</P>
<P>
Much of the Pentagon review concerned calculating possible cost
savings, which Cohen called considerable, from having shipbuilding
engineering, research and development talent concentrated in one
place.
</P>
<P>
But Cohen said planned improvements at Newport News can save
nearly as much money as the merger offered, without a loss in
competition.
</P>
<P>
"While there was still an important differential, we felt that
this differential was not now so great as to override the
management and competitive challenges we could face from the
merger," Cohen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps Up Water, Soil Erosion Control Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- China plans to implement model
water and soil conservation projects nationwide this year to
protect the nation's ecology and promote sustainable development,
China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The initiative will involve model projects for 10 cities, 100
counties and 1,000 small rivers, according to officials with the
Finance and Water Resources ministries.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the projects is to control ecological deterioration
in selected areas within five years, said Vice-Minister of Water
Resources Zhu Dengquan.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for reducing soil erosion in small river valleys
by 70 percent within five years, he added.
</P>
<P>
China has recorded monumental achievements in water and soil
conservation over the past 50 years, with related efforts
effectively controlling serious erosion in areas covering over 780,
000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
China has successfully harnessed 20,000 small rivers, in
addition to tackling soil erosion problems along the nation's
major rivers, including the Yellow and Yangtze rivers, said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
Central government funding for soil erosion control programs
carried out in 1998 was five times greater last year than the
annual amount in recent years, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to increase 1999 funding for soil erosion
control by some 50 million yuan, said Zhang Hongbing, deputy
director of the Agricultural Department under the Ministry of
Finance.
</P>
<P>
Remarkable achievements in water and soil conservancy have not
yet stemmed serious soil erosion and ecological deterioration,
according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He noted that last summer's record flooding along the Yangtze,
Nenjiang and Songhua rivers revealed the serious problems China
continues to face.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
