<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Backs Low Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson said Wednesday that the aim of the Department of
Finance to bring down interest rates to 10 percent within the
first half of the year is realistic.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Post Thursday quoted Singson as saying that the
monetary authorities are supporting the move authored by Finance
Secretary Edgardo Espiritu since this encourages greater economic
activities.
</P>
<P>
"When Secretary Espiritu said they would bring interest rates
to 11 percent by mid-April of this year, I confirmed that,"
Singson said, stressing same support will be given to the new
target.
</P>
<P>
Singson told the newspaper that the Central Bank remains poised
to initiate measures that would pull down lending rates further,
from the prevailing average of about 15 percent which commercial
banks were charging as of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will not tighten our present monetary program because the
need right now is to infuse additional liquidity into the system
to fuel economic growth," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank has already reduced its key overnight rates by
200 basis points since the start of the year and imposed a 3
percent cut in the liquidity reserves requirement for banks,
thereby providing more-than-sufficient funds to "pump-prime" the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Singson reiterated that the Philippines is heading towards a
strong economic resurgence soon as the peso maintains its
stability vis-a-vis the dollar, a lower inflation, and a decline
in interest rates, among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
