<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Says Raids in Kosovo For "Integrated Defense" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema said that Italian warplanes, which carried out an air
strike Wednesday in Kosovo for the first time since NATO's war
against Belgrade, were engaged exclusively in "integrated defense"
tasks.
</P>
<P>
"Italy has not taken part in attacks on Serbian territory, but
it has always taken part in defense actions," he said.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said some of the tasks are to defend Italian troops in
Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
He added that "Italian warplanes are at NATO's disposal to
strike those who shell Albanian territory or those who attack
Macedonian territory, because we obviously have to defend Italian
citizens, both military and civilian, who are operating in those
countries."
</P>
<P>
According to the Italian Defense Ministry, Italian warplanes
bombed military targets over Kosovo Wednesday morning in response
to what the NATO military command felt was "a real threat" to the
allied forces, including the Italian forces present in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The ministry specified that the targets in Kosovo were adjacent
to border areas, and the missions were carried out in accordance
with the "integrated defense principle," which means to protect
Italian and the allies' air space and forces present in the war
zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
