<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Launches War on Rats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will launch a war on
rats nationwide to control diseases transmitted by rats, the
Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 villagers will be hired to help exterminate 20
million rats.
</P>
<P>
The villagers will have to produce dead rats at local health
offices, where tests will be carried out into vermin-related
diseases.
</P>
<P>
The Public Health Ministry is running the project in 28
provinces under the 53-billion-baht (1.4-billion-dollar) job
creation scheme, from which it will draw 24.9 million baht
(673,000 dollars) to pay the rat-catchers.
</P>
<P>
In addition to providing jobless villagers with an income, the
project will improve conditions in communities and help prevent
serious diseases such as leptospirosis, Sutcharit Sripraphan,
acting permanent secretary for health, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that the work will start later this month, prior to
the monsoon breeding season, and will end in September.
</P>
<P>
Leptospirosis, which causes high fever, severe headache,
giddiness or even death, often occurs during the rainy season. It
is transmitted by rat urine and people often contract the disease
when exposed to water accumulated on roads.
</P>
<P>
Thailand reported 1,709 cases of the disease last year, and
among the sick, 84 people died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0292 </DOCNO>
