<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Emphasizing Saving Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- China has increased resource
utilization but saved more resources last year, according to the
Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
At a national meeting on resource conservation recently, it
said that the amount of energy consumed to produce every 10,000
yuan of GDP decreased from 3.55 tons of standard coal in 1996 to 3.
38 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 70 million tons of standard coal, 1.1 million tons
of steel, and 17.37 million cubic meters of timber were saved in
1997.
</P>
<P>
About 316 million tons of industrial solid waste, or 45 percent
of the total, were recycled; waste materials worth 36 billion yuan
(about 4.3 billion US dollars) were recycled in China last year.
</P>
<P>
China earmarked 2.37 billion yuan to support some resource
saving projects as national examples early last year, including a
"green light program" to help reduce electricity consumption.
</P>
<P>
Some experts say that poor management is the major reason for
wasted resources in many enterprises but that some good energy
saving ideas have been introduced to the metallurgical, railway,
and petrochemical industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990415.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues Standards on National Flag Making </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The State Quality and Technical
Supervision Administration issued new standards on national flag
quality to prepare for the celebration of the 50th founding
anniversary of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that the regulations, issued
recently, are the first step taken by the country to forbid
national flag manufacturers from using fabrics made from man-made
fibers.
</P>
<P>
The central and local governments have designated more than 110
manufacturers across the country in accordance with the law to
guarantee high quality flags.
</P>
<P>
China has announced that it would hold a grand military parade
on the National Day, falling on October 1, at the Tian'anmen
Square. Together with other celebrations nationwide, national
flags are badly needed in the market.
</P>
<P>
In the revised quality standards, seams on the flags are no
longer allowed. This requirement applied only to flags measuring
less than two meters in length and width.
</P>
<P>
Li Rucheng, an official with the standardization department,
said: "As symbols of the country, national flags should be
produced using materials like silk and cotton to ensure high
quality."
</P>
<P>
Fabrics of man-made fiber wear out easily and are not suitable
for making national flags, which are mostly hung outdoors, Li
added.
</P>
<P>
He believed that it is within the manufacturers' technical
capability to produce seamless flags. It only takes a slightly
more complicated process along with some more material.
</P>
<P>
Li's administration issued quality standards to regulate the
production of national flags in 1991, one year after the country's
adoption of the Law on National Flag. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
