<HEADLINE> Argentina to Take Tough Measures Against Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem said on Wednesday that he would take all necessary measures
to halt the surge of the crime waves threatening the society.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the local press, Menem said that he would act
with the toughest rigor within the limit of law and called on the
Congress to approve as soon as possible the penal laws requested
by the government.
</P>
<P>
Menem attributed the surge to the consumption of drugs and
television programs full of violence.
</P>
<P>
In the recent rise of crimes mainly in the capital and Greater
Buenos Aires, even high ranking officials were assaulted.
</P>
<P>
Figures show 32.3 percent of the population of Greater Buenos
Aires have fallen victim within the last 12 months, whereas in
January of 1998 this figure was 25.7 percent. 
</P>
