<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Starts Visit to Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ST. JOHN'S, Canada, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji, wrapping up his tour to the United States, arrived in St.
John's on Wednesday to start his seven-day official visit to
Canada to enhance friendship and promote cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
St. John's, capital of Newfoundland province and one of the
oldest cities in North America, gave the Chinese Premier a red-
carpet welcome when he, walking down from his special plane, set
foot on the beautiful Maple Leaf land.
</P>
<P>
Newfoundland's Premier Brian Tobin and Canadian Minister of
Veterans Affair Fred Mifflin were among Canadian officials
greeting Zhu and his wife, Lao An, at the airport.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement delivered at the airport, Premier Zhu
said he was glad to pay the official visit to Canada at the
invitation of Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the fact that China and Canada are tens of thousands
of miles apart, there exists a long history of exchanges and
traditional friendship between our two peoples," Premier Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the joint effort of the two sides, in recent years,
China and Canada have registered significant development with
remarkable achievements in the exchanges and cooperation in
various fields."
</P>
<P>
"To maintain and develop such a sound relationship of
cooperation conforms to the fundamental interests and common
aspirations of our two countries and two peoples, it also serves
peace and prosperity of the Asian-Pacific and the world at large,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu said the Chinese government has all along "attached
importance to developing the friendly relations and cooperation of
equality and mutual benefit with Canada."
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of this visit is to deepen understanding, expand
common ground, enhance friendship and promote cooperation so as to
advance the 21st century-oriented China-Canada partnership of all-
around cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu said he was looking forward to an in-depth exchange
of views with Prime Minister Chretien and other Canadian
government leaders on China-Canada relations and other
international and regional issues of common interest. He was also
looking forward to meeting with more Canadian friends from all
walks of life to exchange views and learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that with concerted efforts of the two sides,
this visit will be crowned with success," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu is scheduled to leave St. John's on Thursday for
Ottawa where he will hold talks with Canadian Prime Minister
Chretien and meet with other Canadian government leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
