<HEADLINE> UEFA to Give Millions to European Clubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- European soccer governing body
UEFA said on Wednesday that it will give back 35 million Swiss
francs (about 23.57 million U.S. dollars) to the sport in the
continent this season.
</P>
<P>
It said a flat sum of 200,000 Swiss francs (134,700 U.S.
dollars) will be paid at the end of the season to all of UEFA's 51
member associations, according to local reports here today.
</P>
<P>
Additional payments will go to clubs eliminated in the two
qualifying phases of the Champions League and all national
champions who did not take part in the competition.
</P>
<P>
Clubs eliminated at, or before, the second round stage of the
Cup Winners' Cup and UEFA Cup also get additional payments.
</P>
<P>
Poland will be the biggest beneficiary, receiving a total of 1.
23 million francs, followed by Romania and Yugoslavia, who will
each receive 1.15 million.
</P>
<P>
San Marino will get 200,000 francs, followed by Liechtenstein
and Andorra with 280,000 and Spain with 360,000. World Cup
champions France get 590,000 francs, England 680,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
