<HEADLINE> Owen Out for Three Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Liverpool and England striker
Michael Owen will miss the next three months with a hamstring and
tendon injury.
</P>
<P>
According to the BBC on Wednesday, the striker has discovered
the shattering results of the scan on his right leg which reveals
far worse damage than was first feared.
</P>
<P>
Owen will miss England's next three matches - the friendly
against Hungary in Budapest on April 28 and the European
Championship qualifiers against Sweden and Bulgaria on June 5 and
9.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool only discovered the real extent of Owen's injury when
they received hospital reports on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Club manager Gerard Houllier said: "The scan has revealed
damage to the hamstring and the tendon. It will take six weeks to
recover from. And then it will take another six weeks after that
to build up the strength in the leg again."
</P>
<P>
Houllier had already decided that Owen would be given a long
rest to recover from the stresses of almost three seasons non-stop
playing before he knew the full extent of the injury.
</P>
<P>
But now the Anfield chief has no option but to write Owen out
of his plans until next season.
</P>
<P>
Owen limped out of Monday's Premiership match at Leeds with a
recurrence of the hamstring injury that has hit him twice before
this season.
</P>
<P>
Now not only will he miss Liverpool's final seven games of the
season, but England's game in Hungary and the two Euro 2000
qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
It is a bitter for England boss Kevin Keegan, who lost Owen
from the Wembley qualifier against Poland last month following an
identical injury picked in the 3-2 defeat at Derby on March 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
