<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Keeps Treble Dream Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- One goal from substitute Ryan
Giggs kept Manchester United's treble dream alive when the team
defeated holders Arsenal 2-1 after extra time at Villa Park on
Wednesday to reach the English F.A. Cup final.
</P>
<P>
In a match of unrelenting drama and incident, United, reduced
to 10 men after skipper Roy Keane was sent off in the 74th minute,
won with a brilliant individual goal from Giggs.
</P>
<P>
Giggs ran 60 meters from inside his own half and rode four
tackles before smashing the ball into the roof of David Seaman's
net.
</P>
<P>
United now play Newcastle United in the Cup Final on May 22 and
keep alive their dream of winning a league and cup double as well
as the European Cup -- a feat never performed by an English club.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal, whose hopes of a second successive cup and league
double died with this defeat, had a golden chance to wrap up the
match up on the stroke of full time but Peter Schmeichel
brilliantly saved Dennis Bergkamp's penalty and sent the match
into extra time.
</P>
<P>
United took the lead after 17 minutes with a superb curling
shot from David Beckham -- the first goal Arsenal had conceeed for
660 minutes since Dieter Hamann of Newcastle scored against them
on February 28.
</P>
<P>
His shot followed a quick inter-passing move with Teddy
Sheringham whose clever reverse flick left Tony Adams stranded and
Beckham in space. His 30-meter shot was always curling away from
his England international colleague Seaman who never came close to
saving the shot.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal equalised in the 69th minute thanks to a lucky
deflection off defender Jaap Stam. Bergkamp's shot was going wide
but hit the knee of his fellow Dutchman and flew past Schmeichel
to level the scores.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal thought they had gone ahead four minutes later when
Schmeichel failed to hold a Bergkamp shot and spilled the ball
into the path of Anelka who led his team mates in wild
celebrations after putting it into the net.
</P>
<P>
But the linesman had already flagged for offside against Anelka
in the build-up to the goal and after a lengthy discussion between
the officials, referee David Elleray disallowed it.
</P>
<P>
United manager Alex Ferguson dropped his 47-goal strike force
of Andy Cole and Dwight Yorke, as well as Giggs from the starting
line-up, but it was Giggs, who came on for Jesper Blomqvist after
an hour, who had the final say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
