<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Appliance Market to Grow in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The development and adoption
of Internet appliances will explode in the United States during
the next 12 months, according to a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
By leveraging the capabilities of the Internet, the report
said, Internet appliances stand ready to revolutionize the way
that information is used and accessed by enabling universal access
-- the ability to access any information, over any network and
from any device.
</P>
<P>
And instead of developing proprietary systems to support the
underlying platform capability necessary to support Internet
appliances, service companies will turn to third-party
infrastructure software and services companies that have begun to
address the unique challenges of the Internet appliance market,
said the report from San Francisco-based Internet Research Group
of the investment bank Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
The group defines Internet appliance as any non-PC device that
leverages the capabilities of the Internet to extend content,
services and applications to the users of those devices. These may
include Internet television, network computer, specialized
hand-held devices with wireless connection to the Internet, and
personal digital assistant (PDA) -- a hand-held computer that
serves as an organizer for personal information.
</P>
<P>
A recent sign of market activity concerning Internet appliances
was announced last week with the agreement between Yahoo and
Online Anywhere. The latter is a provider of products and services
that deliver Web content to television, pagers, cell phones, PDAs
and other non-PC devices. Companies such as America Online,
Microsoft and Excite have also announced initiatives to make
personalized content and services universally accessible to users
regardless of the appliance or type of network they are using to
access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The research group expects traditional access providers, such
as telephone companies, Internet service providers, cable
operators and wireless carriers, to drive the mainstream
acceptance and uptake of Internet appliances. "The winners will be
the service providers that marry the benefits of the Internet with
the specific functions the appliance performs," the group said.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting some of the conclusions, the report said that
contrary to popular belief, Internet appliances will not replace
PCs, but in many cases will provide different services than PCs.
Certain devices, it added, will capture imagination and
enthusiasm, which will add to the viral effect of device adoption.
The power of using the Internet as a vehicle for building
community around a device and its use should not be
underestimated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
