<HEADLINE> Kuwait Bourse Still Near Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wednesday's KSE index was the second lowest in 34 months. On March
21 the bourse hit 1,489.3 points.
</P>
<P>
Regarding other indicators, trading on the KSE also picked up
this week. The average \u}W|9&AMP;=%jtF;o0zb[? .zmillion Kuwaiti
dinars (15.11 million U.S. dollars), compared with 3.38 million
dinars (12.8 million dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
During the past five days, a total of 131.81 million shares were
traded in 3,609 deals, as against 72.89 shares in 1,752 deals in the
four trading days last week.
</P>
<P>
KSE, once one of the most lively stock markets in the Arab world,
has been witnessing a slipping trend since the end of 1997, when its
index ended at 2,651.8 points.
</P>
<P>
The KSE index plunged by more than 1,000 points in 1998 to end
at only 1,582.7 points.
</P>
<P>
Investors and brokers here have attributed the continuing drop
to a lack of confidence in the proposed government economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Facing the sagging oil prices which greatly trimmed the revenues
of a state mainly counting on oil exports, the Kuwaiti government
has been promoting its reform package based price-hikes.
</P>
<P>
But in a country like Kuwait which imposes a cradle-to-grave
welfare policy, it has proved to be a tough job for the government
to ask the people to tighten their belts and live a hard life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
