<HEADLINE> Quayle Officially Declares for U.S. Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Former Vice President Dan
Quayle officially declared his presidential candidacy Wednesday by
pledging to restore integrity and responsibility to the White
House in 2001.
</P>
<P>
"Prosperity without values is no prosperity at all," Quayle
told a cheering crowd of more than 5,000 at his former high
school.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are coming to the end of the dishonest decade of
Bill Clinton and Al Gore, and America needs a fresh start."
</P>
<P>
Quayle promoted his proposed 30 percent across-the-board tax
cut, billing it as a boon to middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
And he portrayed himself as the best qualified potential
commander-in-chief, recalling his participation in White House war
councils and his service on foreign policy committees in the House
and Senate.
</P>
<P>
He accused Clinton and Gore of compromising U.S. sovereignty,
starving the armed forces' budgets and using the military "as a
laboratory for their social experiments."
</P>
<P>
His aides would not say whether Quayle was targeting Bush or
Gore when he declared: "A presidential nomination is not something
that is inherited. It must be earned."
</P>
<P>
Quayle, 52, is a longshot for the nomination despite his
popularity among grassroots activists.
</P>
<P>
He joins a crowded field of social conservative candidates
wrestling over the same votes. His campaign team has come together
slowly. And he raised about 2 million dollars in the first quarter
of 1999 -- 1 million dollars less than projected.
</P>
<P>
His supporters argue that Quayle will easily exceed those low
expectations to sneak up on Bush, who they say can't live up to
his early billing. If the former vice president can emerge from
Iowa and New Hampshire as the choice of social conservatives, his
miscues would fade from memory in the showdown against Bush,
supporters say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
