<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bombing on Yugoslavia Enters 22nd Night </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Air raid sirens went off at
20:40 local time Wednesday over Belgrade, heralding the 22nd night
of NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The capital has been quiet during the day except for a strong
explosion at around 10:00 in the morning, followed by air-raid
sirens shortly after.
</P>
<P>
The sound, it turned out, was possibly the result of sonic boom
from a NATO plane flying over, and the all-clear was sounded about
two and a half hours later.
</P>
<P>
More civilian casualties were reported Wednesday as a result of
NATO air raids.
</P>
<P>
In the most deadliest instance since NATO started its bombings
on March 24, 64 people, including women and children, were
reportedly killed in four waves of NATO air attacks on a convoy of
vehicles with ethnic Albanian refugees returning from the Albanian
border.
</P>
<P>
The convoy, escorted by Yugoslav police, was attacked in broad
daylight at around 13:00 to 15:00 along the Djakovica-Prizren
road, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Today's massacre of ethnic Albanian refugees... has
demonstrated NATO's most brutal aspect," Tanjug quoted Serbian
President Milutinovic as saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Striking four times on refugee convoys cannot be described as
a mistake," the statement said. "It was done on purpose."
</P>
<P>
At around 20:35 Wednesday, NATO launched another wave of
bombing on targets around Pristina, capital of Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
Three missiles hit the city's environs, Tanjug reported, adding
that an air-raid alert had been on in Pristina since Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people gathered on many bridges in Belgrade, Novi
Sad, Sremska Mitrovica, and Zrenjanin as "human shields" against
NATO air raids.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Yugoslav Navy issued an order
Wednesday banning civil navigation in its territorial waters in
the Adriatic Sea and in the inland waterways in Lake Skadar and
the River Bojana.
</P>
<P>
The measure, effective immediately and in force until 05:00
Friday, was necessitated by the complexity of the operations
situation in the Adriatic Sea and intensification of NATO's
threats to the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, Tanjug reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
